les===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of singles showing year released and album name\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:14em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|\"Musty\"\n| rowspan=\"4\"|2017\n| rowspan=\"4\"| ''ShoreLineDoThatShit''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|\"Bottle Service\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|\"Nun Major\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|\"Whuss Da Deal\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|\"Bands\" <small>(with Rob Vicious)</small><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2018/9/shoreline-mafia-rob-vicious-bands-music-video-watch|title=Shoreline Mafia Throw an Over-the-Top Party for New \"Bands\" Video|website=HYPEBEAST|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2018\n| ''Traplantic''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|\"Foreign\"\n|''Party Pack''\n|-\n!! scope=\"row\"|\"Pressure\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2019/2/shoreline-mafia-pressure-music-video-stream|title=Shoreline Mafia Revisit Their 'OTXmas' EP for New \"Pressure\" Video|website=HYPEBEAST|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2019\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''OTXmas''\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"Break Down\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/05/shoreline-mafia-breakdown|title=Hear Shoreline Mafia\u2019s Latest Single 'Breakdown'|website=Complex|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://hellawave.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Atlantic Records artists]]\n[[Category:West Coast hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:American hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2016]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Los Angeles]]\n", "name_user": "Balkanite", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shoreline_Mafia"}
{"title_page": "Tuam", "text_new": "{{distinguish|text = [[Tu'am]], a historical region in [[Eastern Arabia]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|settlement_type        = Town\n|name                   = Tuam\n|native_name            = {{Pad top italic|Tuaim}}\n|native_name_lang       = gle\n|image_skyline          = Tuam High Street 2009 09 14.jpg\n|image_caption          = High Street, looking east\n|image_shield           = Tuam Coat of Arms.svg\n|shield_size            = 155px\n|motto = ''\"Tuath Thuama go Buan\"''<br/>\"Long Live the People of Tuam\"\n|pushpin_map            = Ireland\n|pushpin_label_position = right\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Ireland\n|coordinates            = {{coord|53.515|-8.851|dim:100000_region:IE|display=inline,title}}\n|blank_name_sec1        = Irish Grid Reference\n|blank_info_sec1        = {{iem4ibx|M436521}}\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = Ireland\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Ireland|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Connacht]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Ireland|County]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[County Galway]]\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Municipal district (Ireland)|Municipal District]]\n|subdivision_name3      = Tuam\n|subdivision_type4      = [[D\u00e1il constituencies|D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]]\n|subdivision_name4      = [[Galway East (D\u00e1il constituency)|Galway East]]\n|unit_pref              = Metric\n|elevation_m            = 44\n|area_footnotes         = <ref name=cso2016density>{{cite web | url = http://www.cso.ie/px/pxeirestat/Statire/SelectVarVal/Define.asp?MainTable=E2014&PLanguage=0&PXSId=0 | title = Population Density and Area Size 2016 | publisher = [[Central Statistics Office (Ireland)]] | accessdate = 19 February 2019}}</ref>\n|area_total_km2         = 6.5\n|population_footnotes   = <ref name=cso2016>{{cite web | url = http://census.cso.ie/sapmap2016/Results.aspx?Geog_Type=ST2016&Geog_Code=D9B3E401-47A7-4414-B708-27922B4A1B38 | title = Census 2016 Sapmap Area: Settlements Tuam | publisher = [[Central Statistics Office (Ireland)]] | accessdate = 19 February 2019}}</ref>\n|population_density_km2 = auto\n|population_as_of       = 2016\n|population_total       = 8767\n|population_blank1_title= \n|population_blank1      = \n|area_code_type         = [[Telephone numbers in the Republic of Ireland|Telephone area code]]\n|area_code              = +353(0)93\n|postal_code_type       = [[Eircode]] routing key\n|postal_code            = H54\n|website                = {{URL|tuam-guide.com}}\n}}\n{{Historical populations|state=collapsed\n|1821|4571\n|1831|6883\n|1841|6034\n|1851|4929\n|1861|4563\n|1871|4223\n|1881|3567\n|1891|3012\n|1901|2896\n|1911|2980\n|1926|3293\n|1936|4181\n|1946|3868\n|1951|4010\n|1956|4789\n|1961|4732\n|1966|4742\n|1971|4952\n|1981|6093\n|1986|6039\n|1991|5540\n|1996|5627\n|2002|6027\n|2006|6885\n|2011|8242\n|2016|8767\n| footnote= <ref name=cso2016/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cso.ie/census |title=Census for post 1821 figures. |publisher=Cso.ie |date= |accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref><ref>http://www.histpop.org</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nisranew.nisra.gov.uk/census |title=NISRA \u2013 Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (c) 2013 |publisher=Nisranew.nisra.gov.uk |date=27 September 2010 |accessdate=19 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217095720/http://www.nisranew.nisra.gov.uk/census |archivedate=17 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Lee |first=JJ |authorlink=John Joseph Lee |editor-last=Goldstrom |editor-first=J. M. |editor2-last=Clarkson |editor2-first=L. A. |title=Irish Population, Economy, and Society: Essays in Honour of the Late K. H. Connell |year=1981 |publisher=Clarendon Press |location=Oxford, England |chapter=On the accuracy of the [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Pre-famine]] Irish censuses}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Mokyr |first=Joel |author-link=Joel Mokyr |last2=O Grada |first2=Cormac |author2-link=Cormac \u00d3 Gr\u00e1da |title=New Developments in Irish Population History, 1700\u20131850 |journal=The Economic History Review |volume=37 |issue=4 |pages=473\u2013488 |date=November 1984 |url=http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/journal/120035880/abstract |archive-url=https://archive.today/20121204160709/http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/journal/120035880/abstract |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-12-04 |doi=10.1111/j.1468-0289.1984.tb00344.x }}</ref>\n}}\n'''Tuam''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|tj|u\u02d0|\u0259|m}} {{respell|TEW|\u0259m}}); {{Irish place name|Tuaim|mound or burial-place}} {{IPA-ga|t\u032a\u02e0u\u0259m\u02b2|}})<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.logainm.ie/1411620.aspx | publisher = Irish Placenames Commission | website = logainm.ie | title = Tuaim / Tuam | accessdate = 7 November 2019 }}</ref> is a town in [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] and the second-largest settlement in [[County Galway]]. It is west of the midlands of Ireland, about {{convert|35|km|0|abbr=on}} north of [[Galway]] city. Humans have lived in the area since the [[Prehistoric Ireland#Copper and Bronze Ages (2500\u2013500 BC)|Bronze Age]] while the historic period dates from the 6th century. The town became increasingly important in the 11th and 12th centuries in political and religious aspects of Ireland. The market-based layout of the town and square indicates the importance of commerce.\n\n==History==\nThe record of human settlement in Tuam dates back to the Bronze Age when an area adjacent to Shop Street was used as a burial ground. The name Tuam is a [[cognate]] with the [[Latin]] term [[tumulus]] (burial mound). The town's ancient name was ''Tuaim D\u00e1 Ghualann'', i.e. the burial mound of two shoulders.\n\nThe name probably refers to the high ground on either side of the River Nanny, overlooking a probable fording point over the River Nanny (or Corchra). In 1875, a Bronze Age burial [[urn]] was discovered in the area by workmen, dating from c.1500 B.C.<ref>A Brief History of Tuam. A Town of Two Cathedrals. 2006</ref>\n\nThe history of Tuam as a settlement dates from the early sixth century. Legend states that a monk called [[Iarlaithe mac Loga]] who was a member of a religious community at [[Cloonfush]] some {{convert|6|km|0|abbr=on}} west of Tuam and adjacent to the religious settlement at [[Kilbannon]]. According to the Life of [[Brendan of Clonfert]], Brendan eventually told Iarlaithe \"Not here at all shall be thy resurrection\". When Iarlaithe asked where this may be, Brendan responded: \"Have a new chariot made for thou art old; and go thy way in it, and wherever the two hind shafts of the chariot will break, there will be thy resurrection, and that of many others with thee\".<ref>{{cite book |editor-first=Charles |editor-last=Plummer |title=Lives of Irish Saints |chapter=Life of Brendan of Clonfert |volume=2 |publisher=Oxford University Press |date=1922 |ISBN=0-19-821389-1 |pages=47\u201348}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=P\u00e1draig |last=\u00d3 Riain |title=A Dictionary of Irish Saints |publisher=Four Courts Press |location=Dublin |date=2011 |ISBN=978-1-84682-318-3 |pages=115\u2013116, 374}}</ref> Iarlaithe's wheel broke at Tuam and he established a monastery there, known as the [[School of Tuam]]. As was typical with early settlements in Ireland, religious sites became established first and towns grew around them. Likewise, Tuam grew up around the monastery and has kept the broken chariot wheel as its [[heraldry|heraldic symbol]].\n\nIn 1049, Aedh O'Connor defeated Amalgaid ua Flaithbertaigh, King of [[Iar Connacht]], making the [[O'Conor|O'Connors]] [[list of kings of Connacht|provincial kings of Connacht]]. He then built a castle at Tuam and made it his principal stronghold. This event was directly responsible for the subsequent rise in the importance of the town. Its position dominated the Iar Connacht heartland of [[Maigh Se\u00f3la]].\n\nIn the twelfth century, the town became the centre of Provincial power during the fifty-year reign of [[Tairrdelbach Ua Conchobair]] (r. 1106\u20131156). He also brought Tuam its most prominent status as seat of the [[High King of Ireland]] which he achieved by force of arms during his long career.\n\nAbout 1140 Tairrdelach founded an Augustinian priory in Tuam with possession over three church sites in [[Ciarraige Locha na n\u00c1irne|Ciarraige Airne]], east County Mayo.<ref>See Anne Connon, 'Plotting Acallam na Senorach: the physical context of the 'Mayo' sequence, p85 in Sarah Sheehan [et al.](ed.) Gablanach in Scelaigecht: Celtic studies in honour of Ann Dooley (Dublin, 2013)</ref> At the [[Synod of Kells]] in [[1152 in Ireland|1152]], the centre of government also became the ecclesiastical centre, as Tuam was elevated to an [[Archbishop of Tuam|Archbishopric]], with [[\u00c1ed Ua hOiss\u00edn]] as the first Archbishop.\n\nTairrdelbach Ua Conchobair, as High King of Ireland from [[1128 in Ireland|1128]]\u2013[[1156 in Ireland|1156]], was a great patron of the Irish Church and it was due to his patronage that Tuam became the home of some masterpieces of 12th century Celtic art, including the [[Cross of Cong]]. Tairrdelbach was succeeded by his son [[Ruaidr\u00ed Ua Conchobair]], the last native High King of Ireland. In [[1164 in Ireland|1164]], Ruaidr\u00ed had a \"wonderful castle\" erected, with a large courtyard defended by lofty and massive walls and a deep moat into which the adjacent river was diverted through. This was the first Irish built stone castle.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Gentleman's Magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/gentlemansmagaz304unkngoog|year=1823|publisher=A. Dodd and A. Smith|page=[https://archive.org/details/gentlemansmagaz304unkngoog/page/n361 333]}}</ref> A small part of the castle still stands. Following the destruction of the first Cathedral in [[1184 in Ireland|1184]], [[Ruaidr\u00ed Ua Conchobair]] left Tuam and retired to [[Cong Abbey]], where he entrusted the Church valuables from the Cathedral at Tuam into the care of the abbot. This left Tuam as a small settlement and it wasn't until the early 17th century that it began to grow in importance again.\n\nThroughout history, Tuam has been an important commercial centre with fairs and markets being an important part of commerce in the region. One of its fairs dates to 1252 when Letters Patent were granted to Archbishop MacFlynn by [[Henry III of England]]. Other fairs were authorised by Charters granted by [[James VI and I]] and [[George III of the United Kingdom]].<ref name=autogenerated1>Tuam Official Guide c.1958</ref>\n\nThe [[Annals of the Four Masters]] record that in 1488 \"A whirlwind attacked a number of persons, as they were cutting turf on the bog of Tuaim-Mona, which killed one of them, and swelled the faces of the rest; and four others were killed by the same wind in Machaire-Chonnacht.\"\n\nIn July 1920, the town hall and other properties were burned down by armed [[Royal Irish Constabulary]] men, after two had been killed in an ambush by the [[Irish Republican Army]] near the town the day before.\n\n===Borough of Tuam===\n[[File:Chair_of_Tuam_Monument.JPG|thumb|upright|Chair of Tuam Monument]]\nOn 30 March 1613, Tuam received a royal charter from James VI and I, which enabled the [[Tuam (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Tuam Parliamentary constituency]] to send two representatives to [[Irish House of Commons]] until its abolition in 1800. The town was laid out as a market town to its present plan with all the streets converging on the central square. The charter also established a formal local council with an elected sovereign and 12 burgesses. The sovereign was sworn into office at the site of the \"Chair of Tuam\" which is believed to be within the remaining tower of Ruaidr\u00ed Ua Conchobair's castle. A monumental \"Chair of Tuam\" was unveiled in May 1980 by the late [[Tom\u00e1s \u00d3 Fiaich|Cardinal Tom\u00e1s O'Fiaich]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuam-guide.com/history.htm |title=Tuam History Tuam Galway Tuam County Galway Tuam Ireland Tuaim County Galway |publisher=Tuam-guide.com |date= |accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===High crosses of Tuam===\n[[File:HighCrossTuam01.jpg|left|200px|thumb|High Cross of Tuam]]\n[[File:HeadpieceTuamHighCross.jpg|right|270px|thumb|Headpiece of the High Cross of Tuam]]\nThe High Cross of Tuam was erected in 1152 possibly to commemorate the appointment of the first [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Tuam|Archbishop of Tuam]], Archbishop \u00c1ed Ua hOiss\u00edn. An inscription at the base calls for \"A prayer for O'hOis\u00edn; for the Abbot; by whom it was made\". It is reputed to have been the tallest of the High Crosses of Ireland, but its artistry is scarred by the absence of the top portion of the main shaft.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> The sandstone Cross was originally erected in proximity to the earliest Cathedral erected in the town, a part of which still remains and is incorporated into [[St Mary's Cathedral, Tuam|St Mary's Cathedral]] (12th-century red sandstone chancel arch in Irish [[Romanesque architecture]], which is a National monument). The original High Cross or Market cross may have been erected close to what is now the Market Square and High Street.\n\nWhen the first Cathedral collapsed after being destroyed by fire in 1184, the High Cross was dismantled into pieces, each under different ownership. The archaeologist [[George Petrie (artist)|George Petrie]] discovered the base of the High Cross c. 1820 and later discovered two other pieces in other locations. The High Cross contains a portion from another High Cross, the ringed cross-section on top. In addition to the Market Cross, it is likely that there were at least four other carved stone crosses from the Connor's reign in the town. An area close to the town Square, known as the Shambles, which continued to function as a market place until recently, was at one point the location of the Market Cross until 1721.<ref>[http://www.heritagecouncil.ie/publications/tuam/6.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210052200/http://www.heritagecouncil.ie/publications/tuam/6.html |date=10 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe Cross was brought to Dublin for the Great Exhibition of 1852. However, prior to its return to Tuam, a disagreement arose between the two Churches. Catholic Archbishop Dr. [[John MacHale]] claimed the Cross rightfully belonged to Catholics, with Dean Charles Seymour of the Church of Ireland asserting a Protestant claim. Agreement was reached with the Cross erected half way between both Cathedrals and positioned so that it was visible from all main streets of the town. It was in the Square in the town centre in 1874.\n\nBy the late 1980s, it was evident that the decorative stone carving of the Cross was deteriorating due to weathering and pollution. Experts thought that there was a danger from traffic passing nearby. After lengthy discussions, the Office of Public Works removed the monument from the Square in April 1992. Following cleaning and minor restoration, the High Cross was re-erected in the south transept of St Mary's Cathedral, where it now is, near its original location. St Mary's Cathedral also houses the shaft of a third Cross fashioned from limestone. It is thought that all of the High Crosses would have marked the boundaries of the monastic section of Tuam.\n\n===Coat of arms===\nThe [[Christian cross variants#Forms of the Cross|red latin cross]] is representative of Tuam's importance as an ecclesiastical centre. The double green [[flaunch]]es at the sides, represent the two hills or shoulders of Tuam's ancient name, ''Tuaim Dh\u00e1 Ghualainn''. The two crowns recall the High Kings, Tairrdelbach and Ruaidr\u00ed, who were based in Tuam. The broken chariot wheel being a reminder of the foundation of the monastic town when Iarlaithe's chariot wheel broke. The motto of the town, ''Tuath Thuama go Buan'', translates as \"Long Live the People of Tuam\".<ref>Glimpses of Tuam Since the Famine, J.A. Claffey, {{ISBN|978-0-9530250-0-8}}, 1997, Publisher: Old Tuam Society</ref>\n\n===Bon Secours Mother and Baby Home===\n{{Main article|Bon Secours Mother and Baby Home}}\n\nThe ''Bon Secours Mother and Baby Home'', ''St Mary's Mother and Baby Home'',<ref name=ConnTrib>{{cite news |last1=McNamara |first1=Denise |title=Campaign to recognise 800 dead Tuam babies |url=http://connachttribune.ie/campaign-recognise-800-dead-tuam-babies/ |accessdate=7 June 2014 |work=[[Connacht Tribune]] |date=13 February 2014}}</ref> or simply ''The Home'', was a [[maternity home]] for unmarried mothers and their children that operated between 1925 and 1961 in the town. It was run by the [[Bon Secours Sisters|Bon Secours]] religious order of nuns. From its construction in the mid-19th century until the early 20th century, the building served as a [[workhouse]] for the poor. Excavations carried out between November 2016 and February 2017 that had been ordered by the [[Mother and Baby Homes Commission of Investigation]], under Judge [[Yvonne Murphy]], found a \"significant\" quantity of human remains, aged from 35 foetal weeks to two to three years, interred in a vault with twenty chambers. The report said: \"The Commission has not yet determined what the purpose of this structure was but it appears to be related to the [[septic tank|treatment/containment of sewage and/or waste water]]. The Commission has also not yet determined if it was ever used for this purpose.\" Carbon dating confirmed that the remains date from the timeframe relevant to the operation of the Mother and Baby Home by the Bon Secours order. The Commission stated that it was shocked by the discovery and that it is continuing its investigation into who was responsible for the disposal of human remains in this way.<ref name=\"MBHCOI20170303\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mbhcoi.ie/MBH.nsf/page/Latest%20News-en|title=Notice- 3rd March 2017|publisher=Mother and Baby Homes Commission of Investigation|date=3 March 2017|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\n{{Clear}}\n{{Weather box\n| metric first = yes\n| single line = yes\n| location = Tuam (Airglooney) (1981-2010)\n| Jan high C = 8.7\n| Feb high C = 9.0\n| Mar high C = 10.7\n| Apr high C = 13.0\n| May high C = 15.7\n| Jun high C = 18.3\n| Jul high C = 19.4\n| Aug high C = 19.3\n| Sep high C = 17.3\n| Oct high C = 14.1\n| Nov high C = 11.4\n| Dec high C = 8.9\n| year high C =\n| Jan mean C = 5.2\n| Feb mean C = 5.5\n| Mar mean C = 6.9\n| Apr mean C = 8.4\n| May mean C = 10.9\n| Jun mean C = 13.4\n| Jul mean C = 15.1\n| Aug mean C = 14.9\n| Sep mean C = 12.9\n| Oct mean C = 10.1\n| Nov mean C = 7.8\n| Dec mean C = 5.5\n| year mean C =\n| Jan low C = 1.7\n| Feb low C = 2.0\n| Mar low C = 3.1\n| Apr low C = 3.9\n| May low C = 6.1\n| Jun low C = 8.5\n| Jul low C = 10.8\n| Aug low C = 10.6\n| Sep low C = 8.6\n| Oct low C = 6.0\n| Nov low C = 4.2\n| Dec low C = 2.0\n| year low C =\n|Jan sun = 42.70\n|Feb sun = 61.82\n|Mar sun = 93.31\n|Apr sun = 142.80\n|May sun = 169.26\n|Jun sun = 144.00\n|Jul sun = 126.79\n|Aug sun = 124.93\n|Sep sun = 104.70\n|Oct sun = 86.18\n|Nov sun = 52.80\n|Dec sun = 33.79\n|year sun = \n|source 1 = Met \u00c9ireann<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.met.ie/|title=Met \u00c9ireann Forecast - The Irish Meteorological Service|website=www.met.ie}}</ref>}}\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:Tuam High Street 2009 09 14.jpg|thumb|The High Street in Tuam is the west-most section of the [[N83 road (Ireland)|N83]].]]\nTuam is served by the [[N17 road (Ireland)|N17 road]] (Galway to [[Sligo]]) and the [[N83 road (Ireland)|N83 road]] (to [[Ballyhaunis]]) as well as [[R332 road (Ireland)|R332]] and [[R347 road (Ireland)|R347]]. A bypass of the N17, avoiding congestion to the west of the town, involved acquisition of land by Galway County Council in late 2006. The design of this road includes a bridge over the existing closed railway lines, allowing for future re-opening of the line. The [[M17 road (Ireland)|M17]] was opened ahead of schedule on 27 September 2017.\n\n[[Tuam railway station]] is located on the [[history of rail transport in Ireland|disused railway line]] from Athenry to Sligo. There was a part-successful campaign by West-on-track to have the line reopened as a [[Western Railway Corridor]] which was recognised in the Transport21 project. Construction work to reopen the line between Ennis and Athenry was completed in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westontrack.com/ |title=West=On=Track |publisher=Westontrack.com |date= |accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref> Passengers trains run between Limerick and {{stnlnk|Athenry}} (where connections to Galway can be made) with further extensions planned. Tuam railway station opened on 27 September 1860, closed to passenger traffic on 5 April 1976 and finally closed altogether on 18 December 1978.<ref>{{cite web | title=Tuam station | work=Railscot \u2013 Irish Railways | url=http://www.railscot.co.uk/Ireland/Irish_railways.pdf | accessdate=24 November 2007}}</ref> The railway lines were heavily used by trains transporting sugar beets to the Irish Sugar Factory (Comhlucht Si\u00facra \u00c9ireann Teo.) formerly located off the Ballygaddy Road. The railway line was used during the filming of ''[[The Quiet Man]]'', and can be seen when [[John Wayne]] disembarks at [[Ballyglunin railway station|Ballyglunin]], around 6&nbsp;km (4&nbsp;mi) from Tuam.\n\nTuam is served by multiple [[Bus \u00c9ireann]] routes.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080530135412/http://www.buseireann.ie/pdf/1202290296-64.pdf 25], [https://web.archive.org/web/20080530135414/http://www.buseireann.ie/pdf/1203333408-52.pdf 52], [https://web.archive.org/web/20080530135412/http://www.buseireann.ie/pdf/1202290296-64.pdf 64], [https://web.archive.org/web/20080530135416/http://www.buseireann.ie/pdf/1203333494-417.pdf 417], [https://web.archive.org/web/20080530135409/http://www.buseireann.ie/pdf/1202387484-429.pdf 429], and [https://web.archive.org/web/20080530135407/http://www.buseireann.ie/pdf/1202387485-433.pdf 433].</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Tuam St. Jarlath's College 2009 09 14.jpg|thumb|St Jarlath's College, founded in 1800]]\nTuam is the location of several second level educational institutions, [[St. Jarlath's College]], [[Archbishop McHale College]], Presentation College Currylea and St Bridget's Secondary School. [[St. Patrick's College, Tuam|St Patrick's College]] (formerly Tuam [[List of Christian Brothers schools|Christian Brothers School]]), was amalgamated with St Jarlath's College in June 2009. There are five main primary schools: the Mercy Convent and the Presentation Convent, [[St Patrick's Primary School, Tuam|St Patrick's Primary School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patstuam.ie|title=St Patrick's Primary School - Dublin Road, Tuam.|website=www.patstuam.ie}}</ref> , the Educate Together National School<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tuametns.ie/|title=tuam|website=tuam}}</ref> and Gaelscoil Iarfhlatha, an Irish language primary school (bunscoil l\u00e1n Ghaeilge).\n\n==Economy==\nTuam is home to several large employers, the largest of which is Valeo Vision Systems, which currently employs over 1000 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.valeovision.com/location-general-information|title=Location {{!}} Valeo Vision {{!}}Tuam, Co. Galway|website=www.valeovision.com|language=en|access-date=2017-11-17}}</ref>\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:Tuam Cathedral of the Assumption 2009 09 14.jpg|thumb|Cathedral of the Assumption, built in 1827\u20131837]]\nTuam has two cathedrals, [[Cathedral of the Assumption of the Blessed Virgin Mary, Tuam]], which is the seat of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Tuam]], and the [[Church of Ireland]]'s [[St Mary's Cathedral, Tuam|St Mary's Cathedral]]. The town's [[patron saint]] is [[Iarlaithe mac Loga]]. The ancient monastic site of [[Kilbannon]], founded by [[Benignus of Armagh]] in the 5th century, lies 3.7 km to the northwest of Tuam.\n\n==Sport==\n\n===Gaelic games===\n[[Tuam Stars]], founded in 1888, is the local [[Gaelic football]] team, and are one of Galway's most successful clubs. From 1953 to 1960, Tuam Stars were a dominant force in the Galway County Championship winning seven titles in a row, with players such as [[Se\u00e1n Purcell]] and [[Frank Stockwell]] playing at the time. [[St Jarlath's College]], Tuam has won the [[Hogan Cup]] (national championship for secondary schools) a record 12 times since the competition began in 1946. The parish has a second Gaelic football club, [[Cortoon Shamrocks]], founded in 1888.\n\nTuam Stadium [[St Jarlath's Park]] was officially opened on 21 May 1950 by the Archbishop of Tuam, Rev. Dr. Walsh. It became \"the home of Galway football\" and has hosted many important matches including Connacht Senior Football Finals. A \u20ac5 million redevelopment project has been granted planning permission including a new 6,400 capacity stand and ancillary facilities. Tuam Stadium Development Committee is currently{{when|date=August 2017}} fundraising for this project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuamstadium.com/|title=Tuam Stadium|publisher=|access-date=1 March 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080421124230/http://www.tuamstadium.com/|archive-date=21 April 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Soccer===\nThere are also two local soccer teams: [[Tuam Celtic F.C.|Tuam Celtic A.F.C.]], founded in 1974 who play their home matches at Celtic Park, Cloonthue; and [[Dynamo Blues F.C.|Dynamo Blues]], founded in 1978 whose home is the College Field, Athenry Road.\n\n===Rugby===\nTuam RFC is a rugby union club based on the outskirts of Tuam town in Gurran Park. The club fields two adult junior-standard teams in J1B and J2, senior women's teams, and different youth age groups, both boys and girls. While football was primarily the first choice sport for many, the rugby club has grown annually since its foundation in 1969.\n\n===Golf===\nTuam Golf Club<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuamgolfclub.com/|title=Tuam Golf Club - Golf Courses Galway - Green Fees Ireland|website=www.tuamgolfclub.com}}</ref> was established on 17 October 1904 with the original clubhouse at Cloonascragh on the Athenry Road. The club relocated to Mayfield, on the Dunmore Road in 1937 due to a deterioration of the Cloonascragh course. In March 1940 a new club called the Commercial Golf Club was established, which renovated the course and remained for many years at Cloonascragh. World-renowned Irish golfer [[Christy O'Connor Snr]] joined Tuam Golf Club as club professional in 1948.\n\nTo develop an 18 hole course, [[Tuam Golf Club]] relocated to Barnacurragh (close to the original Cloonascragh course) and a new clubhouse. The first 9 holes were opened in 1975. 18 holes came into play by 1979, on the course designed by golf architect, [[Eddie Hackett]]. Improvement works have continued over the years with [[Christy O'Connor Jnr]] advising the club on course improvement works. The most recent design work has been under the guidance of golf architect Ken Kearney.\n\n===Athletics===\nTuam Athletics Club<ref>[http://www.tuamac.com/ Tuam Athletics Club]</ref> is a thriving and somewhat successful club which, in addition to its many juvenile training sessions, holds training sessions and meets for adults. Tuam is also well known to be the fastest town in Ireland.\n\n===Gymnastics===\nTuam All Star Gymnastics Club runs classes from its Athenry Road base. The club won its first national title in 2002,{{fact|date=November 2019}} and club members have competed internationally.{{fact|date=November 2019}} The club also takes part in local St Patrick's Day parades and Tuam's Summer Arts Festival.{{fact|date=November 2019}} In 2010 the club reached the semi-finals of the [[All Ireland Talent Show]].\n\n===Swimming===\nTuam Swimming Club<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tuamswimclub.com/tuamsc/|title=Tuam Swimming Club|website=tuamswimclub.com}}</ref> has been promoting swimming in the Tuam area since its foundation in 1950. The club season runs from September to the end of June each year.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Arts===\nThe Marian Choral Society was formed in 1974, with an initial aim to sing church and secular music. Then, in 1977, the first musical production was staged, with an annual show each October since.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\nEarwig! Tuam Community Arts Group was formed in October 2003 to provide Tuam and its surroundings with an outlet for its creative talent.{{fact|date=November 2019}} Since 2003, the group has organised an arts festival which includes visual arts, theatre, drama, spectacle, children's arts workshops, street performance and music. Earwig! also takes part in the annual St Patrick's Day parade in Tuam with an emphasis on bringing movement and spectacle.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\n===Music===\nWhile [[The Saw Doctors]] are perhaps the town's most famous band, in the 1960s, Tuam was known as 'The Showband Capital of Ireland'.{{fact|date=November 2019}} At the time, a number of showbands called the market town home, including the Johnny Flynn Showband.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irish-showbands.com/Bands/jflynnf.htm |title=Johnny Flynn Showband |publisher=Irish-showbands.com |date= |accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref> In 2009, a compilation CD of over 50 original songs, all by musicians from Tuam, entitled ''Songs from the Broken Wheel'', was released. Tuam is referenced in song \"[[The Rocky Road to Dublin]]\", popularised by [[The Dubliners]] and various other Irish folk artists. The song details a man's experiences as he travels to [[Liverpool]], England from his home in Tuam.\n\n===Old Tuam Society===\nThe Old Tuam Society was founded in 1942 with a view to preserving a record of the town's past and to foster and promote that knowledge for the benefit of future generations. The new society was open to \"all those who are interested in its aims, namely the preservation and study of the antiquities of Tuam and district.\" An invitation was issued to Tuam people scattered far and wide to join the circle for an annual subscription of two shillings and six pence.<ref>The Tuam Herald, 26 September 1942</ref> The society publishes an annual called ''JOTS'' (''Journal of the Old Tuam Society'').\n\n===Market day===\nThe Tuam market was revived in 2006 by the Energise Tuam, a group which organised by local traders in conjunction with Tuam Chamber of Commerce in an effort to promote shopping in the town. It currently{{when|date=August 2017}} takes place on the last Saturday of every month, at the plaza in front of Tuam Shopping Centre. In the future, Galway County Council has earmarked the Shambles car park nearer the town centre as the market's location on a permanent basis.<ref>[http://www.galwaynews.ie/3230-tuam039s-revived-market-big-success ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721124622/http://www.galwaynews.ie/3230-tuam039s-revived-market-big-success |date=21 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Media===\n''[[The Tuam Herald]]'' is a weekly local newspaper, founded in 1837 by Richard Kelly, which serves the town of Tuam and the surrounding areas of north County Galway, south Mayo and west Roscommon. It is County Galway's oldest newspaper and the fifth oldest newspaper in the Republic of Ireland.<ref>[http://www.regionalnewspapers.ie/paperview.php?id=20 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101019053644/http://www.regionalnewspapers.ie/paperview.php?id=20 |date=19 October 2010 }}</ref>\n\n===Public library===\nTuam Library is on High Street, between Temple Jarlath and St Mary's Cathedral. A collection of general interest and local history books are available for reference along with copies of the ''Tuam Herald'' and the 1901/1911 census on microfilm. Free internet access and Wi-Fi are also available to library users.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\n==International relations==\n{{Main article|List of twin towns and sister cities in the Republic of Ireland}}\n\n===Twin towns===\nTuam is [[town twinning|twinned]] with [[Straubing]] in Germany.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\n==Places of interest==\n[[File:Tuam Teampall Jarlath East Window 2009 09 14.jpg|thumb|13th-century east window of Temple Jarlath]]\n* Temple Jarlath at High Street, marks the site of the earliest monastic settlement in Tuam, established by [[Iarlaithe mac Loga|St Jarlath]] circa 526\u2013527 AD. Temple Jarlath is near the town centre. It marks the site of an early monastic settlement dedicated to St Jarlath, Tuam's 6th century patron. The surviving ruins include a late 13th-century parish church containing an east window in Transitional style.\n* The Mill Museum \u2013 This [[Undershot wheel|undershot]] [[water wheel]] mill found off Shop Street, which traces its origin to the 17th century, was in operation until 1964. It is the only preserved corn mill in the West of Ireland. The Mill Museum complex, located beside the river Nanny, consists of the restored corn mill with operating water wheel, an audiovisual museum and Tourist Information Office.\n* [[Cathedral of the Assumption of the Blessed Virgin Mary, Tuam|Cathedral of the Assumption]] \u2013 [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Tuam]] in [[County Galway]].\n[[File:Tuam St Mary's Cathedral 2009 09 14.jpg|thumb|St Mary's Cathedral]]\n* [[St Mary's Cathedral, Tuam|St Mary's Cathedral]] \u2013 The [[Church of Ireland]] Cathedral was built 1861\u20131878, incorporating a 12th-century arch and sanctuary, and a 14th-century chancel.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Cathedrals of Ireland |last=Galloway |first=Peter |authorlink= Peter Galloway |year=1992 |publisher=The Institute of Irish Studies |location=Belfast |isbn=0-85389-452-3 |pages=210\u2013213}}</ref>\n* [[Castle Hackett|Castlehacket]] \u2013 a castle near Tuam, was home of the Hacket family at first; later of the Kirwans after the Cromwellian settlement. Many scenes from the 1969 movie ''[[Alfred the Great (film)|Alfred the Great]]'' were filmed in the environs of Castlehacket and [[Cnoc Meadha|Knockma]].<ref>Murphy, Mary J. (2008) ''Viking Summer: the Filming of MGM's \"Alfred the Great\" in Galway in 1968'' {{ISBN|978-0-9560749-0-4}}. Hardcover:130 pages, ( Nov 2008). Knockma Publishing.</ref>\n*[[Feartagar Castle]], a [[House of Burke|Burke]] castle located 8 km (5 miles) northwest of Tuam.\n\n==Notable people==\n<!-- Please add entries in alphabetical order by surname -->\n[[File:Tuam Cathedral of the Assumption Statue of Archbishop John MacHale Detail 2009 09 14.jpg|thumb|Statue of John MacHale at the [[Cathedral of the Assumption of the Blessed Virgin Mary, Tuam|Cathedral of the Assumption]]]]\n\n* [[Amergin of Maigh Se\u00f3la]] (fl. c. 550) - father of [[Finbarr of Cork|Saint Finbar]]\n* [[Blaze X]], punk band\n* [[Augustus Nicholas Burke]] (1838-1891) - artist\n* [[Robert Malachy Burke]] (1907-1998) - [[Christian Socialist]], better known as Bobby Burke\n* [[Sir Theobald Burke, 13th Baronet]] (1833-1909) - [[Baronet]] and soldier\n* [[Thomas Henry Burke (civil servant)|Thomas Henry Burke]] (1829-1882) - [[Permanent Under Secretary]] at the [[Chief Secretary for Ireland|Irish Office]]; killed during the [[Phoenix Park Murders]]\n* [[Edward 'Doc' Byrne|Edward \"Doc\" Byrne]] (fl. 1880\u20131884) - author and editor of ''[[The Freeman's Journal]]'' newspaper\n* [[Se\u00e1n Canney]] (b. 1960) - [[Independent Alliance (Ireland)|Independent]] politician and a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] (TD) for the [[Galway East (D\u00e1il constituency)|Galway East]]\n* [[Tairrdelbach Ua Conchobair]] (1088-1156) - [[King of Ireland]]\n* [[Catherine Corless]] (b. 1954) - local historian, Mother and Baby home activist\n* [[Mike Cooley (engineer)|Mike Cooley]] (b. 1934) - trade union activist\n* [[Paul Cunniffe]] (1961-2001) - singer-songwriter, musician\n* [[Bernard Davenport]] (1939-2018) - retired Ambassador to Argentina, also the Holy See\n* [[Raymond Deane]] (b. 1953) - modernist classical composer\n* [[Andrew Egan]] (c.1810-1863) - architect and \"Builder of Tuam\"\n* [[Jarlath Fallon]] (b. 1973) - Gaelic footballer\n* [[R\u00faaidhri Ua Flaithbheartaigh]] (c. 1020-1061) - King of [[Iar Connacht]]\n* [[James Ellis Fleming]] (fl. 1824\u20131832) - claimant to the title of 20th Baron Slane\n* [[\u00c1ed Ua hOiss\u00edn]] (Hugh O'Hession), first Archbishop of Tuam\n* [[Colm Keaveney]] (b. 1971) - politician \n* [[Patrick Kelly (Civil War)|Colonel Patrick Kelly]] - American Civil War Commander\n* [[Mark Killilea Jnr]] - Fianna F\u00e1il politician\n* [[Mark Killilea Snr]] - Fianna Fail politician\n* Sir [[Gerard Lally]] - Irish Jacobite and French military officer\n* [[John MacHale]] - Archbishop of Tuam\n* [[Peter Maher (boxer)|Peter Maher]] - Heavyweight champion boxer\n* [[Jack Mangan]] - Gaelic footballer\n* [[Finian McGrath]] - Independent politician\n* [[Paddy McHugh]] - Independent politician\n* [[Stephen Moore (rugby union)|Stephen Moore]] - Australian International rugby player\n* [[Michael Moran (Tuam)|Michael Moran]] - Republican\n* [[Tom Murphy (playwright)|Tom Murphy]] - playwright\n* [[Brendan Murray]] - member of band [[HomeTown]] and [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Irish 2017 Eurovision]] entrant\n* [[Se\u00e1n \u00d3 Maolalaidh]] - [[Chief of the Name]] (Lally)\n* [[Tom\u00e1s \u00d3 Maolalaidh]] - [[Bishop of Clonmacnoise]] and [[Archbishop of Tuam]]\n* [[Mughron Ua N\u00edoc]] - (d.1032) Abbot of Tuam\n* [[Se\u00e1n Purcell]] - Gaelic footballer\n* [[Frances P. Ruane]] - former director of the [[Economic and Social Research Institute]] (ESRI)\n* [[Mark F. Ryan]] - author and nationalist\n* [[The Saw Doctors]] - band; the [[N17 road (Ireland)|N17]] [[Roads in Ireland|road]] does in fact pass through the town, as their song \"N17\" suggests\n* [[So Cow]] - Irish band\n* [[Frank Stockwell]] - Gaelic footballer\n* [[Brian Talty]] - Gaelic footballer\n\n==Places named after Tuam==\n* Tuam Street, [[Christchurch]], [[New Zealand]] is named after the Irish (Anglican) bishopric of Tuam. It was named by Captain Joseph Thomas, the [[Canterbury Association]]'s Chief Surveyor and his assistant [[Edward Jollie]].<ref>[http://library.christchurch.org.nz/Heritage/PlaceNames/ChristchurchStreetNames-R-Z.pdf Christchurch street names R] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080530135358/http://library.christchurch.org.nz/Heritage/PlaceNames/ChristchurchStreetNames-R-Z.pdf |date=30 May 2008 }}</ref> There are also Tuam Streets located in [[Concord, New South Wales|Concord]], a suburb of Sydney and [[Victoria Park, Western Australia|Victoria Park]], a suburb of [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]], Australia.\n* Tuam Street, in [[Houston]], Texas, US, is named in honour of [[Richard W. Dowling|Richard W. \"Dick\" Dowling]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.texasescapes.com/Houston/Dick-Dowling-Statue-Houston-Texas.htm |title=Dick Dowling Statue, First Public Monument in Houston, Texas |publisher=Texasescapes.com |date= |accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref>\n* Tuamstra\u00dfe (Tuam Street) is located in [[Straubing]], Germany, and is named in honour of the twinning of the two towns.\n* Tuam Road is located [[Plumstead]], in the Borough of [[Royal Borough of Greenwich|Greenwich]] in London, SE18.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londontown.com/LondonStreets/tuam_road_61c.html |title=Tuam Road Guide &#124; Tuam Road, London SE18 &#124; Nearby hotels, shops and restaurants |publisher=LondonTown.com |date=21 October 2013 |accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Diocese of Tuam, Killala and Achonry]]\n*[[List of towns and villages in the Republic of Ireland|List of towns and villages in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Tuam}}\n*{{cite EB1911|wstitle=Tuam |volume=27 |short=x}}\n*[http://www.tuamherald.ie/ Tuam Herald]\n*[http://www.tuam-guide.com/ The Tuam Guide]\n*[http://www.tuamtown.ie/ Tuam Town]\n\n{{County Galway}}\n{{high cross}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Tuam|*]]\n[[Category:High crosses in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Towns and villages in County Galway]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|text = [[Tu'am]], a historical region in [[Eastern Arabia]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|settlement_type        = Town\n|name                   = Tuam\n|native_name            = {{Pad top italic|Tuaim}}\n|native_name_lang       = gle\n|image_skyline          = Tuam High Street 2009 09 14.jpg\n|image_caption          = High Street, looking east\n|image_shield           = Tuam Coat of Arms.svg\n|shield_size            = 155px\n|motto = ''\"Tuath Thuama go Buan\"''<br/>\"Long Live the People of Tuam\"\n|pushpin_map            = Ireland\n|pushpin_label_position = right\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Ireland\n|coordinates            = {{coord|53.515|-8.851|dim:100000_region:IE|display=inline,title}}\n|blank_name_sec1        = Irish Grid Reference\n|blank_info_sec1        = {{iem4ibx|M436521}}\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = Ireland\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Ireland|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Connacht]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Ireland|County]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[County Galway]]\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Municipal district (Ireland)|Municipal District]]\n|subdivision_name3      = Tuam\n|subdivision_type4      = [[D\u00e1il constituencies|D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]]\n|subdivision_name4      = [[Galway East (D\u00e1il constituency)|Galway East]]\n|unit_pref              = Metric\n|elevation_m            = 44\n|area_footnotes         = <ref name=cso2016density>{{cite web | url = http://www.cso.ie/px/pxeirestat/Statire/SelectVarVal/Define.asp?MainTable=E2014&PLanguage=0&PXSId=0 | title = Population Density and Area Size 2016 | publisher = [[Central Statistics Office (Ireland)]] | accessdate = 19 February 2019}}</ref>\n|area_total_km2         = 6.5\n|population_footnotes   = <ref name=cso2016>{{cite web | url = http://census.cso.ie/sapmap2016/Results.aspx?Geog_Type=ST2016&Geog_Code=D9B3E401-47A7-4414-B708-27922B4A1B38 | title = Census 2016 Sapmap Area: Settlements Tuam | publisher = [[Central Statistics Office (Ireland)]] | accessdate = 19 February 2019}}</ref>\n|population_density_km2 = auto\n|population_as_of       = 2016\n|population_total       = 8767\n|population_blank1_title= \n|population_blank1      = \n|area_code_type         = [[Telephone numbers in the Republic of Ireland|Telephone area code]]\n|area_code              = +353(0)93\n|postal_code_type       = [[Eircode]] routing key\n|postal_code            = H54\n|website                = {{URL|tuam-guide.com}}\n}}\n{{Historical populations|state=collapsed\n|1821|4571\n|1831|6883\n|1841|6034\n|1851|4929\n|1861|4563\n|1871|4223\n|1881|3567\n|1891|3012\n|1901|2896\n|1911|2980\n|1926|3293\n|1936|4181\n|1946|3868\n|1951|4010\n|1956|4789\n|1961|4732\n|1966|4742\n|1971|4952\n|1981|6093\n|1986|6039\n|1991|5540\n|1996|5627\n|2002|6027\n|2006|6885\n|2011|8242\n|2016|8767\n| footnote= <ref name=cso2016/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cso.ie/census |title=Census for post 1821 figures. |publisher=Cso.ie |date= |accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref><ref>http://www.histpop.org</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nisranew.nisra.gov.uk/census |title=NISRA \u2013 Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (c) 2013 |publisher=Nisranew.nisra.gov.uk |date=27 September 2010 |accessdate=19 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217095720/http://www.nisranew.nisra.gov.uk/census |archivedate=17 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Lee |first=JJ |authorlink=John Joseph Lee |editor-last=Goldstrom |editor-first=J. M. |editor2-last=Clarkson |editor2-first=L. A. |title=Irish Population, Economy, and Society: Essays in Honour of the Late K. H. Connell |year=1981 |publisher=Clarendon Press |location=Oxford, England |chapter=On the accuracy of the [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Pre-famine]] Irish censuses}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Mokyr |first=Joel |author-link=Joel Mokyr |last2=O Grada |first2=Cormac |author2-link=Cormac \u00d3 Gr\u00e1da |title=New Developments in Irish Population History, 1700\u20131850 |journal=The Economic History Review |volume=37 |issue=4 |pages=473\u2013488 |date=November 1984 |url=http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/journal/120035880/abstract |archive-url=https://archive.today/20121204160709/http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/journal/120035880/abstract |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-12-04 |doi=10.1111/j.1468-0289.1984.tb00344.x }}</ref>\n}}\n'''Tuam''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|tj|u\u02d0|\u0259|m}} {{respell|TEW|\u0259m}}); {{Irish place name|Tuaim|mound or burial-place}} {{IPA-ga|t\u032a\u02e0u\u0259m\u02b2|}})<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.logainm.ie/1411620.aspx | publisher = Irish Placenames Commission | website = logainm.ie | title = Tuaim / Tuam | accessdate = 7 November 2019 }}</ref> is a town in [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] and the second-largest settlement in [[County Galway]]. It is west of the midlands of Ireland, about {{convert|35|km|0|abbr=on}} north of [[Galway]] city. Humans have lived in the area since the [[Prehistoric Ireland#Copper and Bronze Ages (2500\u2013500 BC)|Bronze Age]] while the historic period dates from the 6th century. The town became increasingly important in the 11th and 12th centuries in political and religious aspects of Ireland. The market-based layout of the town and square indicates the importance of commerce.\n\n==History==\nThe record of human settlement in Tuam dates back to the Bronze Age when an area adjacent to Shop Street was used as a burial ground. The name Tuam is a [[cognate]] with the [[Latin]] term [[tumulus]] (burial mound). The town's ancient name was ''Tuaim D\u00e1 Ghualann'', i.e. the burial mound of two shoulders.\n\nThe name probably refers to the high ground on either side of the River Nanny, overlooking a probable fording point over the River Nanny (or Corchra). In 1875, a Bronze Age burial [[urn]] was discovered in the area by workmen, dating from c.1500 B.C.<ref>A Brief History of Tuam. A Town of Two Cathedrals. 2006</ref>\n\nThe history of Tuam as a settlement dates from the early sixth century. Legend states that a monk called [[Iarlaithe mac Loga]] who was a member of a religious community at [[Cloonfush]] some {{convert|6|km|0|abbr=on}} west of Tuam and adjacent to the religious settlement at [[Kilbannon]]. According to the Life of [[Brendan of Clonfert]], Brendan eventually told Iarlaithe \"Not here at all shall be thy resurrection\". When Iarlaithe asked where this may be, Brendan responded: \"Have a new chariot made for thou art old; and go thy way in it, and wherever the two hind shafts of the chariot will break, there will be thy resurrection, and that of many others with thee\".<ref>{{cite book |editor-first=Charles |editor-last=Plummer |title=Lives of Irish Saints |chapter=Life of Brendan of Clonfert |volume=2 |publisher=Oxford University Press |date=1922 |ISBN=0-19-821389-1 |pages=47\u201348}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=P\u00e1draig |last=\u00d3 Riain |title=A Dictionary of Irish Saints |publisher=Four Courts Press |location=Dublin |date=2011 |ISBN=978-1-84682-318-3 |pages=115\u2013116, 374}}</ref> Iarlaithe's wheel broke at Tuam and he established a monastery there, known as the [[School of Tuam]]. As was typical with early settlements in Ireland, religious sites became established first and towns grew around them. Likewise, Tuam grew up around the monastery and has kept the broken chariot wheel as its [[heraldry|heraldic symbol]].\n\nIn 1049, Aedh O'Connor defeated Amalgaid ua Flaithbertaigh, King of [[Iar Connacht]], making the [[O'Conor|O'Connors]] [[list of kings of Connacht|provincial kings of Connacht]]. He then built a castle at Tuam and made it his principal stronghold. This event was directly responsible for the subsequent rise in the importance of the town. Its position dominated the Iar Connacht heartland of [[Maigh Se\u00f3la]].\n\nIn the twelfth century, the town became the centre of Provincial power during the fifty-year reign of [[Tairrdelbach Ua Conchobair]] (r. 1106\u20131156). He also brought Tuam its most prominent status as seat of the [[High King of Ireland]] which he achieved by force of arms during his long career.\n\nAbout 1140 Tairrdelach founded an Augustinian priory in Tuam with possession over three church sites in [[Ciarraige Locha na n\u00c1irne|Ciarraige Airne]], east County Mayo.<ref>See Anne Connon, 'Plotting Acallam na Senorach: the physical context of the 'Mayo' sequence, p85 in Sarah Sheehan [et al.](ed.) Gablanach in Scelaigecht: Celtic studies in honour of Ann Dooley (Dublin, 2013)</ref> At the [[Synod of Kells]] in [[1152 in Ireland|1152]], the centre of government also became the ecclesiastical centre, as Tuam was elevated to an [[Archbishop of Tuam|Archbishopric]], with [[\u00c1ed Ua hOiss\u00edn]] as the first Archbishop.\n\nTairrdelbach Ua Conchobair, as High King of Ireland from [[1128 in Ireland|1128]]\u2013[[1156 in Ireland|1156]], was a great patron of the Irish Church and it was due to his patronage that Tuam became the home of some masterpieces of 12th century Celtic art, including the [[Cross of Cong]]. Tairrdelbach was succeeded by his son [[Ruaidr\u00ed Ua Conchobair]], the last native High King of Ireland. In [[1164 in Ireland|1164]], Ruaidr\u00ed had a \"wonderful castle\" erected, with a large courtyard defended by lofty and massive walls and a deep moat into which the adjacent river was diverted through. This was the first Irish built stone castle.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Gentleman's Magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/gentlemansmagaz304unkngoog|year=1823|publisher=A. Dodd and A. Smith|page=[https://archive.org/details/gentlemansmagaz304unkngoog/page/n361 333]}}</ref> A small part of the castle still stands. Following the destruction of the first Cathedral in [[1184 in Ireland|1184]], [[Ruaidr\u00ed Ua Conchobair]] left Tuam and retired to [[Cong Abbey]], where he entrusted the Church valuables from the Cathedral at Tuam into the care of the abbot. This left Tuam as a small settlement and it wasn't until the early 17th century that it began to grow in importance again.\n\nThroughout history, Tuam has been an important commercial centre with fairs and markets being an important part of commerce in the region. One of its fairs dates to 1252 when Letters Patent were granted to Archbishop MacFlynn by [[Henry III of England]]. Other fairs were authorised by Charters granted by [[James VI and I]] and [[George III of the United Kingdom]].<ref name=autogenerated1>Tuam Official Guide c.1958</ref>\n\nThe [[Annals of the Four Masters]] record that in 1488 \"A whirlwind attacked a number of persons, as they were cutting turf on the bog of Tuaim-Mona, which killed one of them, and swelled the faces of the rest; and four others were killed by the same wind in Machaire-Chonnacht.\"\n\nIn July 1920, the town hall and other properties were burned down by armed [[Royal Irish Constabulary]] men, after two had been killed in an ambush by the [[Irish Republican Army]] near the town the day before.\n\n===Borough of Tuam===\n[[File:Chair_of_Tuam_Monument.JPG|thumb|upright|Chair of Tuam Monument]]\nOn 30 March 1613, Tuam received a royal charter from James VI and I, which enabled the [[Tuam (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Tuam Parliamentary constituency]] to send two representatives to [[Irish House of Commons]] until its abolition in 1800. The town was laid out as a market town to its present plan with all the streets converging on the central square. The charter also established a formal local council with an elected sovereign and 12 burgesses. The sovereign was sworn into office at the site of the \"Chair of Tuam\" which is believed to be within the remaining tower of Ruaidr\u00ed Ua Conchobair's castle. A monumental \"Chair of Tuam\" was unveiled in May 1980 by the late [[Tom\u00e1s \u00d3 Fiaich|Cardinal Tom\u00e1s O'Fiaich]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuam-guide.com/history.htm |title=Tuam History Tuam Galway Tuam County Galway Tuam Ireland Tuaim County Galway |publisher=Tuam-guide.com |date= |accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===High crosses of Tuam===\n[[File:HighCrossTuam01.jpg|left|200px|thumb|High Cross of Tuam]]\n[[File:HeadpieceTuamHighCross.jpg|right|270px|thumb|Headpiece of the High Cross of Tuam]]\nThe High Cross of Tuam was erected in 1152 possibly to commemorate the appointment of the first [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Tuam|Archbishop of Tuam]], Archbishop \u00c1ed Ua hOiss\u00edn. An inscription at the base calls for \"A prayer for O'hOis\u00edn; for the Abbot; by whom it was made\". It is reputed to have been the tallest of the High Crosses of Ireland, but its artistry is scarred by the absence of the top portion of the main shaft.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> The sandstone Cross was originally erected in proximity to the earliest Cathedral erected in the town, a part of which still remains and is incorporated into [[St Mary's Cathedral, Tuam|St Mary's Cathedral]] (12th-century red sandstone chancel arch in Irish [[Romanesque architecture]], which is a National monument). The original High Cross or Market cross may have been erected close to what is now the Market Square and High Street.\n\nWhen the first Cathedral collapsed after being destroyed by fire in 1184, the High Cross was dismantled into pieces, each under different ownership. The archaeologist [[George Petrie (artist)|George Petrie]] discovered the base of the High Cross c. 1820 and later discovered two other pieces in other locations. The High Cross contains a portion from another High Cross, the ringed cross-section on top. In addition to the Market Cross, it is likely that there were at least four other carved stone crosses from the Connor's reign in the town. An area close to the town Square, known as the Shambles, which continued to function as a market place until recently, was at one point the location of the Market Cross until 1721.<ref>[http://www.heritagecouncil.ie/publications/tuam/6.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210052200/http://www.heritagecouncil.ie/publications/tuam/6.html |date=10 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe Cross was brought to Dublin for the Great Exhibition of 1852. However, prior to its return to Tuam, a disagreement arose between the two Churches. Catholic Archbishop Dr. [[John MacHale]] claimed the Cross rightfully belonged to Catholics, with Dean Charles Seymour of the Church of Ireland asserting a Protestant claim. Agreement was reached with the Cross erected half way between both Cathedrals and positioned so that it was visible from all main streets of the town. It was in the Square in the town centre in 1874.\n\nBy the late 1980s, it was evident that the decorative stone carving of the Cross was deteriorating due to weathering and pollution. Experts thought that there was a danger from traffic passing nearby. After lengthy discussions, the Office of Public Works removed the monument from the Square in April 1992. Following cleaning and minor restoration, the High Cross was re-erected in the south transept of St Mary's Cathedral, where it now is, near its original location. St Mary's Cathedral also houses the shaft of a third Cross fashioned from limestone. It is thought that all of the High Crosses would have marked the boundaries of the monastic section of Tuam.\n\n===Coat of arms===\nThe [[Christian cross variants#Forms of the Cross|red latin cross]] is representative of Tuam's importance as an ecclesiastical centre. The double green [[flaunch]]es at the sides, represent the two hills or shoulders of Tuam's ancient name, ''Tuaim Dh\u00e1 Ghualainn''. The two crowns recall the High Kings, Tairrdelbach and Ruaidr\u00ed, who were based in Tuam. The broken chariot wheel being a reminder of the foundation of the monastic town when Iarlaithe's chariot wheel broke. The motto of the town, ''Tuath Thuama go Buan'', translates as \"Long Live the People of Tuam\".<ref>Glimpses of Tuam Since the Famine, J.A. Claffey, {{ISBN|978-0-9530250-0-8}}, 1997, Publisher: Old Tuam Society</ref>\n\n===Bon Secours Mother and Baby Home===\n{{Main article|Bon Secours Mother and Baby Home}}\n\nThe ''Bon Secours Mother and Baby Home'', ''St Mary's Mother and Baby Home'',<ref name=ConnTrib>{{cite news |last1=McNamara |first1=Denise |title=Campaign to recognise 800 dead Tuam babies |url=http://connachttribune.ie/campaign-recognise-800-dead-tuam-babies/ |accessdate=7 June 2014 |work=[[Connacht Tribune]] |date=13 February 2014}}</ref> or simply ''The Home'', was a [[maternity home]] for unmarried mothers and their children that operated between 1925 and 1961 in the town. It was run by the [[Bon Secours Sisters|Bon Secours]] religious order of nuns. From its construction in the mid-19th century until the early 20th century, the building served as a [[workhouse]] for the poor. Excavations carried out between November 2016 and February 2017 that had been ordered by the [[Mother and Baby Homes Commission of Investigation]], under Judge [[Yvonne Murphy]], found a \"significant\" quantity of human remains, aged from 35 foetal weeks to two to three years, interred in a vault with twenty chambers. The report said: \"The Commission has not yet determined what the purpose of this structure was but it appears to be related to the [[septic tank|treatment/containment of sewage and/or waste water]]. The Commission has also not yet determined if it was ever used for this purpose.\" Carbon dating confirmed that the remains date from the timeframe relevant to the operation of the Mother and Baby Home by the Bon Secours order. The Commission stated that it was shocked by the discovery and that it is continuing its investigation into who was responsible for the disposal of human remains in this way.<ref name=\"MBHCOI20170303\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mbhcoi.ie/MBH.nsf/page/Latest%20News-en|title=Notice- 3rd March 2017|publisher=Mother and Baby Homes Commission of Investigation|date=3 March 2017|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\n{{Clear}}\n{{Weather box\n| metric first = yes\n| single line = yes\n| location = Tuam (Airglooney) (1981-2010)\n| Jan high C = 8.7\n| Feb high C = 9.0\n| Mar high C = 10.7\n| Apr high C = 13.0\n| May high C = 15.7\n| Jun high C = 18.3\n| Jul high C = 19.4\n| Aug high C = 19.3\n| Sep high C = 17.3\n| Oct high C = 14.1\n| Nov high C = 11.4\n| Dec high C = 8.9\n| year high C =\n| Jan mean C = 5.2\n| Feb mean C = 5.5\n| Mar mean C = 6.9\n| Apr mean C = 8.4\n| May mean C = 10.9\n| Jun mean C = 13.4\n| Jul mean C = 15.1\n| Aug mean C = 14.9\n| Sep mean C = 12.9\n| Oct mean C = 10.1\n| Nov mean C = 7.8\n| Dec mean C = 5.5\n| year mean C =\n| Jan low C = 1.7\n| Feb low C = 2.0\n| Mar low C = 3.1\n| Apr low C = 3.9\n| May low C = 6.1\n| Jun low C = 8.5\n| Jul low C = 10.8\n| Aug low C = 10.6\n| Sep low C = 8.6\n| Oct low C = 6.0\n| Nov low C = 4.2\n| Dec low C = 2.0\n| year low C =\n|Jan sun = 42.70\n|Feb sun = 61.82\n|Mar sun = 93.31\n|Apr sun = 142.80\n|May sun = 169.26\n|Jun sun = 144.00\n|Jul sun = 126.79\n|Aug sun = 124.93\n|Sep sun = 104.70\n|Oct sun = 86.18\n|Nov sun = 52.80\n|Dec sun = 33.79\n|year sun = \n|source 1 = Met \u00c9ireann<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.met.ie/|title=Met \u00c9ireann Forecast - The Irish Meteorological Service|website=www.met.ie}}</ref>}}\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:Tuam High Street 2009 09 14.jpg|thumb|The High Street in Tuam is the west-most section of the [[N83 road (Ireland)|N83]].]]\nTuam is served by the [[N17 road (Ireland)|N17 road]] (Galway to [[Sligo]]) and the [[N83 road (Ireland)|N83 road]] (to [[Ballyhaunis]]) as well as [[R332 road (Ireland)|R332]] and [[R347 road (Ireland)|R347]]. A bypass of the N17, avoiding congestion to the west of the town, involved acquisition of land by Galway County Council in late 2006. The design of this road includes a bridge over the existing closed railway lines, allowing for future re-opening of the line. The [[M17 road (Ireland)|M17]] was opened ahead of schedule on 27 September 2017.\n\n[[Tuam railway station]] is located on the [[history of rail transport in Ireland|disused railway line]] from Athenry to Sligo. There was a part-successful campaign by West-on-track to have the line reopened as a [[Western Railway Corridor]] which was recognised in the Transport21 project. Construction work to reopen the line between Ennis and Athenry was completed in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westontrack.com/ |title=West=On=Track |publisher=Westontrack.com |date= |accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref> Passengers trains run between Limerick and {{stnlnk|Athenry}} (where connections to Galway can be made) with further extensions planned. Tuam railway station opened on 27 September 1860, closed to passenger traffic on 5 April 1976 and finally closed altogether on 18 December 1978.<ref>{{cite web | title=Tuam station | work=Railscot \u2013 Irish Railways | url=http://www.railscot.co.uk/Ireland/Irish_railways.pdf | accessdate=24 November 2007}}</ref> The railway lines were heavily used by trains transporting sugar beets to the Irish Sugar Factory (Comhlucht Si\u00facra \u00c9ireann Teo.) formerly located off the Ballygaddy Road. The railway line was used during the filming of ''[[The Quiet Man]]'', and can be seen when [[John Wayne]] disembarks at [[Ballyglunin railway station|Ballyglunin]], around 6&nbsp;km (4&nbsp;mi) from Tuam.\n\nTuam is served by multiple [[Bus \u00c9ireann]] routes.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080530135412/http://www.buseireann.ie/pdf/1202290296-64.pdf 25], [https://web.archive.org/web/20080530135414/http://www.buseireann.ie/pdf/1203333408-52.pdf 52], [https://web.archive.org/web/20080530135412/http://www.buseireann.ie/pdf/1202290296-64.pdf 64], [https://web.archive.org/web/20080530135416/http://www.buseireann.ie/pdf/1203333494-417.pdf 417], [https://web.archive.org/web/20080530135409/http://www.buseireann.ie/pdf/1202387484-429.pdf 429], and [https://web.archive.org/web/20080530135407/http://www.buseireann.ie/pdf/1202387485-433.pdf 433].</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Tuam St. Jarlath's College 2009 09 14.jpg|thumb|St Jarlath's College, founded in 1800]]\nTuam is the location of several second level educational institutions, [[St. Jarlath's College]], [[Archbishop McHale College]], Presentation College Currylea and St Bridget's Secondary School. [[St. Patrick's College, Tuam|St Patrick's College]] (formerly Tuam [[List of Christian Brothers schools|Christian Brothers School]]), was amalgamated with St Jarlath's College in June 2009. There are five main primary schools: the Mercy Convent and the Presentation Convent, [[St Patrick's Primary School, Tuam|St Patrick's Primary School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patstuam.ie|title=St Patrick's Primary School - Dublin Road, Tuam.|website=www.patstuam.ie}}</ref> , the Educate Together National School<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tuametns.ie/|title=tuam|website=tuam}}</ref> and Gaelscoil Iarfhlatha, an Irish language primary school (bunscoil l\u00e1n Ghaeilge).\n\n==Economy==\nTuam is home to several large employers, the largest of which is Valeo Vision Systems, which currently employs over 1000 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.valeovision.com/location-general-information|title=Location {{!}} Valeo Vision {{!}}Tuam, Co. Galway|website=www.valeovision.com|language=en|access-date=2017-11-17}}</ref>\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:Tuam Cathedral of the Assumption 2009 09 14.jpg|thumb|Cathedral of the Assumption, built in 1827\u20131837]]\nTuam has two cathedrals, [[Cathedral of the Assumption of the Blessed Virgin Mary, Tuam]], which is the seat of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Tuam]], and the [[Church of Ireland]]'s [[St Mary's Cathedral, Tuam|St Mary's Cathedral]]. The town's [[patron saint]] is [[Iarlaithe mac Loga]]. The ancient monastic site of [[Kilbannon]], founded by [[Benignus of Armagh]] in the 5th century, lies 3.7 km to the northwest of Tuam.\n\n==Sport==\n\n===Gaelic games===\n[[Tuam Stars]], founded in 1888, is the local [[Gaelic football]] team, and are one of Galway's most successful clubs. From 1953 to 1960, Tuam Stars were a dominant force in the Galway County Championship winning seven titles in a row, with players such as [[Se\u00e1n Purcell]] and [[Frank Stockwell]] playing at the time. [[St Jarlath's College]], Tuam has won the [[Hogan Cup]] (national championship for secondary schools) a record 12 times since the competition began in 1946. The parish has a second Gaelic football club, [[Cortoon Shamrocks]], founded in 1888.\n\nTuam Stadium [[St Jarlath's Park]] was officially opened on 21 May 1950 by the Archbishop of Tuam, Rev. Dr. Walsh. It became \"the home of Galway football\" and has hosted many important matches including Connacht Senior Football Finals. A \u20ac5 million redevelopment project has been granted planning permission including a new 6,400 capacity stand and ancillary facilities. Tuam Stadium Development Committee is currently{{when|date=August 2017}} fundraising for this project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuamstadium.com/|title=Tuam Stadium|publisher=|access-date=1 March 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080421124230/http://www.tuamstadium.com/|archive-date=21 April 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Soccer===\nThere are also two local soccer teams: [[Tuam Celtic F.C.|Tuam Celtic A.F.C.]], founded in 1974 who play their home matches at Celtic Park, Cloonthue; and [[Dynamo Blues F.C.|Dynamo Blues]], founded in 1978 whose home is the College Field, Athenry Road.\n\n===Rugby===\nTuam RFC is a rugby union club based on the outskirts of Tuam town in Gurran Park. The club fields two adult junior-standard teams in J1B and J2, senior women's teams, and different youth age groups, both boys and girls. While football was primarily the first choice sport for many, the rugby club has grown annually since its foundation in 1969.\n\n===Golf===\nTuam Golf Club<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuamgolfclub.com/|title=Tuam Golf Club - Golf Courses Galway - Green Fees Ireland|website=www.tuamgolfclub.com}}</ref> was established on 17 October 1904 with the original clubhouse at Cloonascragh on the Athenry Road. The club relocated to Mayfield, on the Dunmore Road in 1937 due to a deterioration of the Cloonascragh course. In March 1940 a new club called the Commercial Golf Club was established, which renovated the course and remained for many years at Cloonascragh. World-renowned Irish golfer [[Christy O'Connor Snr]] joined Tuam Golf Club as club professional in 1948.\n\nTo develop an 18 hole course, [[Tuam Golf Club]] relocated to Barnacurragh (close to the original Cloonascragh course) and a new clubhouse. The first 9 holes were opened in 1975. 18 holes came into play by 1979, on the course designed by golf architect, [[Eddie Hackett]]. Improvement works have continued over the years with [[Christy O'Connor Jnr]] advising the club on course improvement works. The most recent design work has been under the guidance of golf architect Ken Kearney.\n\n===Athletics===\nTuam Athletics Club<ref>[http://www.tuamac.com/ Tuam Athletics Club]</ref> is a thriving and somewhat successful club which, in addition to its many juvenile training sessions, holds training sessions and meets for adults.\n\n===Gymnastics===\nTuam All Star Gymnastics Club runs classes from its Athenry Road base. The club won its first national title in 2002,{{fact|date=November 2019}} and club members have competed internationally.{{fact|date=November 2019}} The club also takes part in local St Patrick's Day parades and Tuam's Summer Arts Festival.{{fact|date=November 2019}} In 2010 the club reached the semi-finals of the [[All Ireland Talent Show]].\n\n===Swimming===\nTuam Swimming Club<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tuamswimclub.com/tuamsc/|title=Tuam Swimming Club|website=tuamswimclub.com}}</ref> has been promoting swimming in the Tuam area since its foundation in 1950. The club season runs from September to the end of June each year.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Arts===\nThe Marian Choral Society was formed in 1974, with an initial aim to sing church and secular music. Then, in 1977, the first musical production was staged, with an annual show each October since.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\nEarwig! Tuam Community Arts Group was formed in October 2003 to provide Tuam and its surroundings with an outlet for its creative talent.{{fact|date=November 2019}} Since 2003, the group has organised an arts festival which includes visual arts, theatre, drama, spectacle, children's arts workshops, street performance and music. Earwig! also takes part in the annual St Patrick's Day parade in Tuam with an emphasis on bringing movement and spectacle.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\n===Music===\nWhile [[The Saw Doctors]] are perhaps the town's most famous band, in the 1960s, Tuam was known as 'The Showband Capital of Ireland'.{{fact|date=November 2019}} At the time, a number of showbands called the market town home, including the Johnny Flynn Showband.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irish-showbands.com/Bands/jflynnf.htm |title=Johnny Flynn Showband |publisher=Irish-showbands.com |date= |accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref> In 2009, a compilation CD of over 50 original songs, all by musicians from Tuam, entitled ''Songs from the Broken Wheel'', was released. Tuam is referenced in song \"[[The Rocky Road to Dublin]]\", popularised by [[The Dubliners]] and various other Irish folk artists. The song details a man's experiences as he travels to [[Liverpool]], England from his home in Tuam.\n\n===Old Tuam Society===\nThe Old Tuam Society was founded in 1942 with a view to preserving a record of the town's past and to foster and promote that knowledge for the benefit of future generations. The new society was open to \"all those who are interested in its aims, namely the preservation and study of the antiquities of Tuam and district.\" An invitation was issued to Tuam people scattered far and wide to join the circle for an annual subscription of two shillings and six pence.<ref>The Tuam Herald, 26 September 1942</ref> The society publishes an annual called ''JOTS'' (''Journal of the Old Tuam Society'').\n\n===Market day===\nThe Tuam market was revived in 2006 by the Energise Tuam, a group which organised by local traders in conjunction with Tuam Chamber of Commerce in an effort to promote shopping in the town. It currently{{when|date=August 2017}} takes place on the last Saturday of every month, at the plaza in front of Tuam Shopping Centre. In the future, Galway County Council has earmarked the Shambles car park nearer the town centre as the market's location on a permanent basis.<ref>[http://www.galwaynews.ie/3230-tuam039s-revived-market-big-success ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721124622/http://www.galwaynews.ie/3230-tuam039s-revived-market-big-success |date=21 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Media===\n''[[The Tuam Herald]]'' is a weekly local newspaper, founded in 1837 by Richard Kelly, which serves the town of Tuam and the surrounding areas of north County Galway, south Mayo and west Roscommon. It is County Galway's oldest newspaper and the fifth oldest newspaper in the Republic of Ireland.<ref>[http://www.regionalnewspapers.ie/paperview.php?id=20 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101019053644/http://www.regionalnewspapers.ie/paperview.php?id=20 |date=19 October 2010 }}</ref>\n\n===Public library===\nTuam Library is on High Street, between Temple Jarlath and St Mary's Cathedral. A collection of general interest and local history books are available for reference along with copies of the ''Tuam Herald'' and the 1901/1911 census on microfilm. Free internet access and Wi-Fi are also available to library users.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\n==International relations==\n{{Main article|List of twin towns and sister cities in the Republic of Ireland}}\n\n===Twin towns===\nTuam is [[town twinning|twinned]] with [[Straubing]] in Germany.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\n==Places of interest==\n[[File:Tuam Teampall Jarlath East Window 2009 09 14.jpg|thumb|13th-century east window of Temple Jarlath]]\n* Temple Jarlath at High Street, marks the site of the earliest monastic settlement in Tuam, established by [[Iarlaithe mac Loga|St Jarlath]] circa 526\u2013527 AD. Temple Jarlath is near the town centre. It marks the site of an early monastic settlement dedicated to St Jarlath, Tuam's 6th century patron. The surviving ruins include a late 13th-century parish church containing an east window in Transitional style.\n* The Mill Museum \u2013 This [[Undershot wheel|undershot]] [[water wheel]] mill found off Shop Street, which traces its origin to the 17th century, was in operation until 1964. It is the only preserved corn mill in the West of Ireland. The Mill Museum complex, located beside the river Nanny, consists of the restored corn mill with operating water wheel, an audiovisual museum and Tourist Information Office.\n* [[Cathedral of the Assumption of the Blessed Virgin Mary, Tuam|Cathedral of the Assumption]] \u2013 [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Tuam]] in [[County Galway]].\n[[File:Tuam St Mary's Cathedral 2009 09 14.jpg|thumb|St Mary's Cathedral]]\n* [[St Mary's Cathedral, Tuam|St Mary's Cathedral]] \u2013 The [[Church of Ireland]] Cathedral was built 1861\u20131878, incorporating a 12th-century arch and sanctuary, and a 14th-century chancel.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Cathedrals of Ireland |last=Galloway |first=Peter |authorlink= Peter Galloway |year=1992 |publisher=The Institute of Irish Studies |location=Belfast |isbn=0-85389-452-3 |pages=210\u2013213}}</ref>\n* [[Castle Hackett|Castlehacket]] \u2013 a castle near Tuam, was home of the Hacket family at first; later of the Kirwans after the Cromwellian settlement. Many scenes from the 1969 movie ''[[Alfred the Great (film)|Alfred the Great]]'' were filmed in the environs of Castlehacket and [[Cnoc Meadha|Knockma]].<ref>Murphy, Mary J. (2008) ''Viking Summer: the Filming of MGM's \"Alfred the Great\" in Galway in 1968'' {{ISBN|978-0-9560749-0-4}}. Hardcover:130 pages, ( Nov 2008). Knockma Publishing.</ref>\n*[[Feartagar Castle]], a [[House of Burke|Burke]] castle located 8 km (5 miles) northwest of Tuam.\n\n==Notable people==\n<!-- Please add entries in alphabetical order by surname -->\n[[File:Tuam Cathedral of the Assumption Statue of Archbishop John MacHale Detail 2009 09 14.jpg|thumb|Statue of John MacHale at the [[Cathedral of the Assumption of the Blessed Virgin Mary, Tuam|Cathedral of the Assumption]]]]\n\n* [[Amergin of Maigh Se\u00f3la]] (fl. c. 550) - father of [[Finbarr of Cork|Saint Finbar]]\n* [[Blaze X]], punk band\n* [[Augustus Nicholas Burke]] (1838-1891) - artist\n* [[Robert Malachy Burke]] (1907-1998) - [[Christian Socialist]], better known as Bobby Burke\n* [[Sir Theobald Burke, 13th Baronet]] (1833-1909) - [[Baronet]] and soldier\n* [[Thomas Henry Burke (civil servant)|Thomas Henry Burke]] (1829-1882) - [[Permanent Under Secretary]] at the [[Chief Secretary for Ireland|Irish Office]]; killed during the [[Phoenix Park Murders]]\n* [[Edward 'Doc' Byrne|Edward \"Doc\" Byrne]] (fl. 1880\u20131884) - author and editor of ''[[The Freeman's Journal]]'' newspaper\n* [[Se\u00e1n Canney]] (b. 1960) - [[Independent Alliance (Ireland)|Independent]] politician and a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] (TD) for the [[Galway East (D\u00e1il constituency)|Galway East]]\n* [[Tairrdelbach Ua Conchobair]] (1088-1156) - [[King of Ireland]]\n* [[Catherine Corless]] (b. 1954) - local historian, Mother and Baby home activist\n* [[Mike Cooley (engineer)|Mike Cooley]] (b. 1934) - trade union activist\n* [[Paul Cunniffe]] (1961-2001) - singer-songwriter, musician\n* [[Bernard Davenport]] (1939-2018) - retired Ambassador to Argentina, also the Holy See\n* [[Raymond Deane]] (b. 1953) - modernist classical composer\n* [[Andrew Egan]] (c.1810-1863) - architect and \"Builder of Tuam\"\n* [[Jarlath Fallon]] (b. 1973) - Gaelic footballer\n* [[R\u00faaidhri Ua Flaithbheartaigh]] (c. 1020-1061) - King of [[Iar Connacht]]\n* [[James Ellis Fleming]] (fl. 1824\u20131832) - claimant to the title of 20th Baron Slane\n* [[\u00c1ed Ua hOiss\u00edn]] (Hugh O'Hession), first Archbishop of Tuam\n* [[Colm Keaveney]] (b. 1971) - politician \n* [[Patrick Kelly (Civil War)|Colonel Patrick Kelly]] - American Civil War Commander\n* [[Mark Killilea Jnr]] - Fianna F\u00e1il politician\n* [[Mark Killilea Snr]] - Fianna Fail politician\n* Sir [[Gerard Lally]] - Irish Jacobite and French military officer\n* [[John MacHale]] - Archbishop of Tuam\n* [[Peter Maher (boxer)|Peter Maher]] - Heavyweight champion boxer\n* [[Jack Mangan]] - Gaelic footballer\n* [[Finian McGrath]] - Independent politician\n* [[Paddy McHugh]] - Independent politician\n* [[Stephen Moore (rugby union)|Stephen Moore]] - Australian International rugby player\n* [[Michael Moran (Tuam)|Michael Moran]] - Republican\n* [[Tom Murphy (playwright)|Tom Murphy]] - playwright\n* [[Brendan Murray]] - member of band [[HomeTown]] and [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017|Irish 2017 Eurovision]] entrant\n* [[Se\u00e1n \u00d3 Maolalaidh]] - [[Chief of the Name]] (Lally)\n* [[Tom\u00e1s \u00d3 Maolalaidh]] - [[Bishop of Clonmacnoise]] and [[Archbishop of Tuam]]\n* [[Mughron Ua N\u00edoc]] - (d.1032) Abbot of Tuam\n* [[Se\u00e1n Purcell]] - Gaelic footballer\n* [[Frances P. Ruane]] - former director of the [[Economic and Social Research Institute]] (ESRI)\n* [[Mark F. Ryan]] - author and nationalist\n* [[The Saw Doctors]] - band; the [[N17 road (Ireland)|N17]] [[Roads in Ireland|road]] does in fact pass through the town, as their song \"N17\" suggests\n* [[So Cow]] - Irish band\n* [[Frank Stockwell]] - Gaelic footballer\n* [[Brian Talty]] - Gaelic footballer\n\n==Places named after Tuam==\n* Tuam Street, [[Christchurch]], [[New Zealand]] is named after the Irish (Anglican) bishopric of Tuam. It was named by Captain Joseph Thomas, the [[Canterbury Association]]'s Chief Surveyor and his assistant [[Edward Jollie]].<ref>[http://library.christchurch.org.nz/Heritage/PlaceNames/ChristchurchStreetNames-R-Z.pdf Christchurch street names R] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080530135358/http://library.christchurch.org.nz/Heritage/PlaceNames/ChristchurchStreetNames-R-Z.pdf |date=30 May 2008 }}</ref> There are also Tuam Streets located in [[Concord, New South Wales|Concord]], a suburb of Sydney and [[Victoria Park, Western Australia|Victoria Park]], a suburb of [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]], Australia.\n* Tuam Street, in [[Houston]], Texas, US, is named in honour of [[Richard W. Dowling|Richard W. \"Dick\" Dowling]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.texasescapes.com/Houston/Dick-Dowling-Statue-Houston-Texas.htm |title=Dick Dowling Statue, First Public Monument in Houston, Texas |publisher=Texasescapes.com |date= |accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref>\n* Tuamstra\u00dfe (Tuam Street) is located in [[Straubing]], Germany, and is named in honour of the twinning of the two towns.\n* Tuam Road is located [[Plumstead]], in the Borough of [[Royal Borough of Greenwich|Greenwich]] in London, SE18.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londontown.com/LondonStreets/tuam_road_61c.html |title=Tuam Road Guide &#124; Tuam Road, London SE18 &#124; Nearby hotels, shops and restaurants |publisher=LondonTown.com |date=21 October 2013 |accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Diocese of Tuam, Killala and Achonry]]\n*[[List of towns and villages in the Republic of Ireland|List of towns and villages in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Tuam}}\n*{{cite EB1911|wstitle=Tuam |volume=27 |short=x}}\n*[http://www.tuamherald.ie/ Tuam Herald]\n*[http://www.tuam-guide.com/ The Tuam Guide]\n*[http://www.tuamtown.ie/ Tuam Town]\n\n{{County Galway}}\n{{high cross}}\n\