r skin dark and giving them a dry cough. It spread to China after contracted by a local Chinese restaurant returning home to celebrate the Chinese New Year. And later became a global pandemic blamed on bats and Wuhan chicken.\n\n==Surrounding Communities==\nLincoln Place has four borders, including the Pittsburgh neighborhoods of [[Hays (Pittsburgh)|Hays]] to the northwest and [[New Homestead (Pittsburgh)|New Homestead]] to the north, and the boroughs of [[Munhall, Pennsylvania|Munhall]] to the northeast and [[West Mifflin]] to the east, south and west.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090401083953/http://www.city.pittsburgh.pa.us/cp/maps/flash.html Interactive Pittsburgh Neighborhoods Map]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080402081157/http://www.city.pittsburgh.pa.us/cp/maps/lincoln_place.html Lincoln Place Map]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Pittsburgh neighborhoods]]\n\n\n{{Pittsburgh, Allegheny County, Pennsylvania}}\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Pittsburgh]]\n", "name_user": "73.154.128.198", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(removed malicious content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lincoln_Place_(Pittsburgh)"}
{"title_page": "72nd Street station (New York Central Railroad)", "text_new": "{{Infobox station\n | name=72nd Street\n | style=New York Central Railroad\n | image=Staircase leading to the abandoned 72nd Street station in the Park Avenue Tunnel.jpg\n | image_size=\n | image_caption=This picture was taken from the southwestern corner of Park Avenue and 72nd Street. The emergency exit\u2013the former staircase leading to the southbound platform\u2013is open to allow workers to do lighting work in the tunnel.\n | address=[[Park Avenue]] and 72nd Street<br/>[[Upper East Side]], [[Manhattan]], [[New York (state)|New York]] \n | coordinates={{coord|40.771125|-73.963825|type:railwaystation_region:US-NY|display=inline,title}}\n | line = [[Park Avenue main line|Park Avenue Tunnel (Hudson Line)]]\n | other=\n | platform=2 side\n | tracks=4\n | parking=\n | bicycle=\n | passengers=\n | pass_year=\n | pass_percent=\n | opened=\n | closed=\n | rebuilt=\n | ADA=\n | code=\n | owned=\n | zone=\n | other_services_header=Former services\n | other_services= {{Adjacent stations|system=New York Central Railroad|line=Harlem Division|left=86th Street|right=59th Street|to-left=Chatham|to-right=New York}}\n | map_locator=\n}}\n\nThe '''72nd Street station''' is an abandoned station located in the [[Park Avenue Tunnel (railroad)|Park Avenue Tunnel]] used by [[Metro-North Railroad]] for all of its trains. The station has two side platforms and is located in between [[72nd Street (Manhattan)|72nd Street]] and 73rd Street underneath [[Park Avenue]] on the [[Upper East Side]] of [[Manhattan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://catalog.archives.gov/OpaAPI/media/6082347/content/arcmedia/cartographic/gallery/6082347.pdf|title=Track Map for the New York & Harlem Railroad Operated by the New York Central Railroad Company|last=|first=|date=June 30, 1917|website=archives.gov|publisher=Interstate Commerce Commission. Bureau of Valuation, Engineering Section.|access-date=December 27, 2018}}</ref> The station was built by the [[New York Central & Hudson River Railroad]] as part of an agreement with [[New York City]].\n\n== History ==\nThe station was built during the late 19th century, and it is unclear if any regular trains actually stopped here. Currently, the station is used as an emergency exit for [[Metro-North Railroad]] in the Park Avenue Tunnel. The staircases are intact and can be accessed from Park Avenue.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.canadasouthern.com/caso/ett/images/electric-tt-1241.pdf|title=Electric Division New York Terminal District Time-Table No. 54A For Employees Only|last=|first=|last2=|date=December 14, 1941|website=canadasouthern.com|publisher=New York Central Railroad|access-date=}}</ref>{{Rp|10, 72}} According to an 1895 timetable, two trains stopped at 72nd Street daily to serve students attending what is now [[Hunter College]].<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.columbia.edu/~brennan/abandoned/86st.html|title=86 St (Park Ave)|last=Brennan|first=Joseph|date=2002|website=Columbia University|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.columbia.edu:80/~brennan/beach/chapter13.html|title=\"THE UNDERGROUND RAILWAY, NEW YORK CITY\" 1875|last=Brennan|first=Joseph|website=Columbia University|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504110641/http://www.columbia.edu/~brennan/beach/chapter13.html|archive-date=May 4, 2009|url-status=dead|access-date=October 9, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/13/realestate/13scapes.html|title=When Vanderbilt Did Not Get His Way|last=Gray|first=Christopher|date=September 10, 2009|website=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref> On April 29, 1901, the New York Central was granted permission to abandon this station and the [[86th Street station (New York Central Railroad)|86th Street station]] by the New York State Railroad Commissioners. The station had low ridership.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%25209%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Sun%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Sun%25201901%2520Grayscale%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Sun%25201901%2520Jan-Dec%2520Grayscale%2520-%25201618.pdf%23xml%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3D4f31edf%26DocId%3D3270378%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cindex%2520O%252dG%252dT%26HitCount%3D3%26hits%3D1952%2B1953%2B1954%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&uri=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%25209%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Sun%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Sun%25201901%2520Grayscale%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Sun%25201901%2520Jan-Dec%2520Grayscale%2520-%25201618.pdf&xml=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3D4f31edf%26DocId%3D3270378%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cindex%2520O%252dG%252dT%26HitCount%3D3%26hits%3D1952%2B1953%2B1954%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&openFirstHlPage=false|title=Railroad Projects Heard: Harlem Road to Abandon Seventy-second and Eighty-sixth Street Stations.|last=|first=|date=April 30, 1901|work=The New York Sun|access-date=December 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct railway stations in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Former New York Central Railroad stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Park Avenue]]\n[[Category:Upper East Side]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox station\n | name=72nd Street\n | style=New York Central Railroad\n | image=Staircase leading to the abandoned 72nd Street station in the Park Avenue Tunnel.jpg\n | image_size=\n | image_caption=This picture was taken from the southwestern corner of Park Avenue and 72nd Street. The emergency exit\u2013the former staircase leading to the southbound platform\u2013is open to allow workers to do lighting work in the tunnel.\n | address=[[Park Avenue]] and 72nd Street<br/>[[Upper East Side]], [[Manhattan]], [[New York (state)|New York]] \n | coordinates={{coord|40.771125|-73.963825|type:railwaystation_region:US-NY|display=inline,title}}\n | line = [[Park Avenue main line|Park Avenue Tunnel (Hudson Line)]]\n | other=\n | platform=2 side\n | tracks=4\n | parking=\n | bicycle=\n | passengers=\n | pass_year=\n | pass_percent=\n | opened=\n | closed=\n | rebuilt=\n | ADA=\n | code=\n | owned=\n | zone=\n | other_services_header=Former services\n | other_services= {{Adjacent stations|system=New York Central Railroad|line=Harlem Division|left=86th Street|right=59th Street|to-left=Chatham|to-right=New York}}\n | map_locator=\n}}\n\nThe '''72nd Street station''' is an abandoned station located in the [[Park Avenue Tunnel (railroad)|Park Avenue Tunnel]] used by [[Metro-North Railroad]] for all of its trains. The station has two side platforms and is located in between [[72nd Street]] and 73rd Street underneath [[Park Avenue]] on the [[Upper East Side]] of [[Manhattan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://catalog.archives.gov/OpaAPI/media/6082347/content/arcmedia/cartographic/gallery/6082347.pdf|title=Track Map for the New York & Harlem Railroad Operated by the New York Central Railroad Company|last=|first=|date=June 30, 1917|website=archives.gov|publisher=Interstate Commerce Commission. Bureau of Valuation, Engineering Section.|access-date=December 27, 2018}}</ref> The station was built by the [[New York Central & Hudson River Railroad]] as part of an agreement with [[New York City]].\n\n== History ==\nThe station was built during the late 19th century, and it is unclear if any regular trains actually stopped here. Currently, the station is used as an emergency exit for [[Metro-North Railroad]] in the Park Avenue Tunnel. The staircases are intact and can be accessed from Park Avenue.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.canadasouthern.com/caso/ett/images/electric-tt-1241.pdf|title=Electric Division New York Terminal District Time-Table No. 54A For Employees Only|last=|first=|last2=|date=December 14, 1941|website=canadasouthern.com|publisher=New York Central Railroad|access-date=}}</ref>{{Rp|10, 72}} According to an 1895 timetable, two trains stopped at 72nd Street daily to serve students attending what is now [[Hunter College]].<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.columbia.edu/~brennan/abandoned/86st.html|title=86 St (Park Ave)|last=Brennan|first=Joseph|date=2002|website=Columbia University|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.columbia.edu:80/~brennan/beach/chapter13.html|title=\"THE UNDERGROUND RAILWAY, NEW YORK CITY\" 1875|last=Brennan|first=Joseph|website=Columbia University|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504110641/http://www.columbia.edu/~brennan/beach/chapter13.html|archive-date=May 4, 2009|url-status=dead|access-date=October 9, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/13/realestate/13scapes.html|title=When Vanderbilt Did Not Get His Way|last=Gray|first=Christopher|date=September 10, 2009|website=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref> On April 29, 1901, the New York Central was granted permission to abandon this station and the [[86th Street station (New York Central Railroad)|86th Street station]] by the New York State Railroad Commissioners. The station had low ridership.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%25209%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Sun%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Sun%25201901%2520Grayscale%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Sun%25201901%2520Jan-Dec%2520Grayscale%2520-%25201618.pdf%23xml%3Dhttp%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3D4f31edf%26DocId%3D3270378%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cindex%2520O%252dG%252dT%26HitCount%3D3%26hits%3D1952%2B1953%2B1954%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&uri=http%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%25209%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Sun%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Sun%25201901%2520Grayscale%2FNew%2520York%2520NY