{"title_page": "Terrific (comics)", "text_new": "{{Infobox comic book title <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics--> \n|title= Terrific \n|image= Terrific4.jpg\n|imagesize=\n|caption= Cover of the fourth issue of ''Terrific'', dating from 6 May 1967\n|schedule=\n|ongoing =Y\n|publisher=[[Odhams Press]]' [[Power Comics]]\n|date=15 April 1967 \u2013 3 February 1968 (merged with ''[[Fantastic_(comics)|Fantastic]]'')\n| issues = 43\n|Superhero=y\n|main_char_team= [[Avengers (comics)|The Avengers]]<br />[[Doctor Strange]]<br />[[Sub-Mariner]]<br />[[Giant-Man]]\n|writers= \n|artists= \n|pencillers=\n|inkers=\n|letterers=\n|colorists=\n|editors=\n|creative_team_month=\n|creative_team_year=\n|creators=\n|subcat=\n|sort=Pow\n|nonUS=y\n}}\n'''''Terrific''''' was a weekly [[British comic]] published by [[Odhams Press]]' [[Power Comics]] imprint in 1967\u20131968. ''Terrific'' was similar in format to its sister title ''Fantastic'', which had started publication two months earlier. The two titles were quite unlike other British comics of the time, consisting mainly of material reprinted from American [[Marvel Comics]]. In this respect they can be considered a precursor of the [[Marvel UK]] weeklies, such as ''[[The Mighty World of Marvel]]'', that appeared during the 1970s.\n\n''Terrific'' ran for 43 issues from 15 April 1967 until 3 February 1968, when it was merged with ''[[Fantastic_(comics)|Fantastic]]''.\n\nThe Marvel titles which were reprinted in ''Terrific'' included ''[[Avengers (comics)|The Avengers]]'', the [[Doctor Strange]] strips from ''[[Strange Tales]]'', and the [[Sub-Mariner]] and [[Giant-Man]] strips from ''[[Tales to Astonish]]''.\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.internationalhero.co.uk/m/marvuk.htm History of Marvel UK]\n* [http://www.26pigs.com/terrific/index.html The Power Comics: Terrific]\n* [http://myweb.tiscali.co.uk/bridip/clitheroe/links2.htm#comics 1960s British Comics review]\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Terrific (Comic)}}\n[[Category:1967 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:British comics magazines]]\n[[Category:Defunct British comics]]\n[[Category:Fleetway and IPC Comics titles]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1967]]\n[[Category:Magazines disestablished in 1968]]\n\n{{UK-comics-stub}}\n{{italic title}}\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Terrific4.jpg|right|thumb|Cover of the fourth issue of ''Terrific'', dating from 6 May 1967]]'''''Terrific''''' was a weekly [[British comic]] published by [[Odhams Press]] under the [[Power Comics]] imprint. It ran for 43 issues from 15 April 1967 until 3 February 1968, when it was merged with its sister title ''[[Fantastic_(comics)|Fantastic]]''.\n\n''Terrific'' was very similar in format to ''Fantastic'', which had started publication two months earlier. The two titles were quite unlike other British comics of the time, consisting mainly of material reprinted from American [[Marvel Comics]]. In this respect they can be considered a precursor of the [[Marvel UK]] weeklies, such as ''[[The Mighty World of Marvel]]'', that appeared during the 1970s.\n\nThe Marvel titles which were reprinted in ''Terrific'' included ''[[Avengers (comics)|The Avengers]]'', the [[Doctor Strange]] strips from ''[[Strange Tales]]'', and the [[Sub-Mariner]] and [[Giant-Man]] strips from ''[[Tales to Astonish]]''.\n\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.internationalhero.co.uk/m/marvuk.htm History of Marvel UK]\n* [http://www.26pigs.com/terrific/index.html The Power Comics: Terrific]\n* [http://myweb.tiscali.co.uk/bridip/clitheroe/links2.htm#comics 1960s British Comics review]\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Terrific (Comic)}}\n[[Category:1967 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:British comics magazines]]\n[[Category:Defunct British comics]]\n[[Category:Fleetway and IPC Comics titles]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1967]]\n[[Category:Magazines disestablished in 1968]]\n\n{{UK-comics-stub}}\n{{italic title}}\n", "name_user": "Stoshmaster", "label": "safe", "comment": "infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terrific_(comics)"}
{"title_page": "Changuu", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Prison Island|the type of prison|Prison island}}\n{{Infobox islands\n| name = Changuu\n| image_name = Topographic map of Zanzibar-en.svg\n| image_caption = Unguja and surrounding islands\n| map         = Tanzania\n| map_caption = \n| nickname = \n| location = [[Indian Ocean]]\n| additional_info = \n| coordinates = {{coord|6|7|9.81|S|39|9|56.06|E|type:isle_region:TZ-15|display=title,inline}}\n| archipelago = [[Zanzibar Archipelago]]\n| total_islands =\n| major_islands =\n| area_km2 = \n| length_km = 0.8\n| width_km = 0.23\n| highest_mount = \n| elevation_m = \n| population = \n| population_as_of =\n| density_km2 =\n| ethnic_groups =\n| country_admin_divisions_title     = Region\n| country_admin_divisions           = [[Zanzibar]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_1   =\n| country_admin_divisions_1         =\n| country_admin_divisions_title_2   =\n| country_admin_divisions_2         =\n| country_capital_city              = \n| country_largest_city              = \n| country_largest_city_population   =\n| country_leader_title              =\n| country_leader_name               =\n}}\n'''Changuu Island''' (also known as '''Kibandiko''', '''Prison''' or '''Quarantine Island''') is a small island 5.6&nbsp;km northwest of [[Stone Town]], [[Unguja]], [[Zanzibar]].  The island is around 800m long and 230m wide at its broadest point.<ref name=\"private\"/>  The island saw use as a prison for rebellious slaves in 1860s and also functioned as a [[coral]] mine.  \n\nThe [[United Kingdom|British]] [[First Minister]] of Zanzibar, [[Lloyd Mathews]], purchased the island in 1893 and constructed a prison complex there.  No prisoners were ever housed on the island and instead it became a [[quarantine]] station for [[yellow fever]] cases.  The station was only occupied for around half of the year and the rest of the time it was a popular holiday destination.  More recently, the island has become a government-owned tourist resort and houses a collection of endangered [[Aldabra giant tortoise]]s which were originally a gift from the [[United Kingdom|British]] governor of the [[Seychelles]].\n[[File:Prison island.jpg|The Island as seen from the Indian Ocean|thumb|800px|left]]\n\n== History ==\nChanguu is named after the [[Swahili language|Swahili]] name of a fish which is common in the seas around it, though it is shown as \"Kibandiko Island\" on some older maps, but this name is no longer used.<ref name=\"private\">{{cite web  | last = Changuu Private Island Paradise  | title = History  | url = http://www.privateislands-zanzibar.com/changuu/changuu-private-island-history.php  | accessdate = 2008-03-13  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080322213233/http://www.privateislands-zanzibar.com/changuu/changuu-private-island-history.php  | archive-date = 2008-03-22  | url-status = dead  }}</ref><ref name=\"travel\"/>  The island was uninhabited until the 1860s when the first [[Sultan of Zanzibar|Sultan]] of Zanzibar, [[Majid bin Said of Zanzibar|Majid bin Said]], gave it to two [[Arab]]s who used it as a prison for rebellious slaves prior to shipping them abroad or selling them at the slave market in Zanzibar's [[Stone Town]].<ref name=\"tourist\">{{cite web  | last = Zanzibar Commission for Tourism |title=Dhow Cruising  | url = http://www.zanzibartourism.net/dhowcruising.php | accessdate = 2008-03-15}}</ref>  \n\nZanzibar became a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[protectorate]] following the 1890 [[Heligoland-Zanzibar Treaty]] with [[Germany]], this resulted in the appointment of a British [[First Minister]], [[Lloyd Mathews]], in October 1891.<ref name=\"pouwels164\">{{Harvnb|Pouwels|1987|p=164}}.</ref><ref name=\"DNB\">{{Cite encyclopedia |last=Milne |first=Lynne  |contribution=Lloyd Mathews |title=[[Dictionary of National Biography]] |contribution-url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/34936 |ref=harv}}</ref>  Mathews purchased Changuu from its Arab owners on behalf of the Zanzibar government in 1893 with the intention of building a prison upon it.<ref name=\"private\"/>  The prison was to have housed violent and [[recidivism|recidivist]] criminals from the part of the African mainland which was then under the jurisdiction of Zanzibar.<ref name=\"tourist\"/>  Despite the prison buildings being completed in 1894, causing the island to become known commonly as \"Prison Island\", the facility never housed prisoners.<ref name=\"private\"/>\n\nThe British authorities were concerned by the risk of disease epidemics affecting Stone Town, then [[East Africa]]'s main port.  To combat this threat Changuu was turned into a [[quarantine]] island serving all of the British territories in East Africa.  The old prison was converted into the facility's hospital and in 1923 the island was officially renamed Quarantine Island.<ref name=\"private\"/>  Quarantine cases would be taken from the ships and monitored on the island for between one and two weeks before being allowed to progress with their journey.<ref name=\"travel\">{{cite web  | last = McIntyre  | first = Chris  | authorlink =   | coauthors =   | title = Islands near Zanzibar Town| work =   Zanzibar Travel Guide| publisher = Bradt Travel Guides  | year = 2006  | url = http://www.zanzibar-travel-guide.com/bradt_guide.asp?bradt=1918 | format =   | doi =   | accessdate = 2008-03-13}}</ref>  The main disease that was monitored was [[Yellow Fever]].<ref name=\"tourist\"/>  \n\nShips typically only arrived in East Africa during the period running from December to March and so the island was usually empty of quarantine cases for a large part of the year.<ref name=\"private\"/>  During the empty period the island became a popular leisure resort for European people and local residents of Zanzibar.  A building, known as the European Bungalow, was built in the late 1890s to cater for the holiday makers although the number of visitors had to be limited as the only freshwater on the island was rainwater stored in underground tanks.<ref name=\"private\"/>  Large pits on the island remained from earlier coral mining for use as a construction material and these pits were cleaned out and used as swimming pools.<ref name=\"travel\"/>  A new complex of quarantine buildings was erected in the south-west of the island in 1931 which gave an improved quarantine capacity of 904 persons.<ref name=\"private\"/>\n\n== Giant tortoises ==\n[[File:Aldabra giant tortoises on Changuu.jpg|Giant tortoises on the Island|thumb]]\n[[File:Aldabra Giant Tortoise Geochelone gigantea edit1.jpg|thumb|right|An Aldabra giant tortoise from Zanzibar]]\nIn 1919 the British governor of [[Seychelles]] sent a gift of four [[Aldabra giant tortoise]]s to Changuu from the island of [[Aldabra]].<ref name=\"private\"/>  These tortoises bred quickly and by 1955 they numbered around 200 animals.  However people began to steal the tortoises for sale abroad as pets or for food and their numbers dropped rapidly.  By 1988 there were around 100 tortoises, fifty in 1990 and just seven by 1996.<ref name=\"travel\"/>  A further 80 hatchlings were taken to the island in 1996 to increase the numbers but 40 of them vanished.  The Zanzibar government, with assistance from the [[World Society for the Protection of Animals]] (Now known as [[World Animal Protection]]) built a large compound for the protection of the animals and by 2000 numbers had recovered to 17 adults, 50 juveniles and 90 hatchlings.  \n\nThe species is now considered [[Vulnerable species|vulnerable]] and has been placed on the [[IUCN Red List]] by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]].  More tortoises, mainly juveniles, continue to be brought to the island from other locations for conservation.<ref name=\"travel\"/>  There is a dedicated foundation on the island which looks after the tortoises' welfare.<ref name=\"private\"/>  Visitors are able to observe and feed the tortoises.<ref name=\"travel\"/>\n\n== Changuu today ==\n\nThe island lost its use as a quarantine station, but remained in the ownership of the government who converted the newer quarantine buildings into a guesthouse.<ref name=\"private\"/>  This ceased to function but has since been reopened as a hotel by a private company.<ref name=\"travel\"/>  There are 15 holiday cottages in the northwest of the island as well as a tennis court, swimming pool and library and the old European Bungalow has been turned into a restaurant named after Mathews.<ref name=\"private\"/>  Freshwater is transported to the island via an underwater pipe from the Zanzibar mainland.<ref name=\"private\"/>  \n\nThe island is still owned by the government, which charges a US$4 entry fee.<ref name=\"travel\"/>  The old prison remains standing, providing shelter for some of the tortoises and the cells can be visited.<ref name=\"tourist\"/><ref name=\"planet\">{{cite web  | last = Planet Aware  | title = Changuu Island| url = http://www.planetware.com/zanzibar/changuu-island-tza-zza-chang.htm  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320073118/http://www.planetware.com/zanzibar/changuu-island-tza-zza-chang.htm|archivedate=2012-03-20|accessdate=2015-05-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{Cite book|last1=Pouwels|first1=Randall L|title=Horn and Crescent: Cultural Change and Traditional Islam on the East African Coast, 800-1900|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|year=1987|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iyw-_NMk0bgC|isbn=0-521-52309-5|ref=harv|postscript=<!--None-->}}.\n\n[[Category:Islands of Zanzibar]]\n[[Category:Zanzibar City]]\n[[Category:Prison islands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox islands\n| name = Changuu\n| image_name = Topographic map of Zanzibar-en.svg\n| image_caption = Unguja and surrounding islands\n| map         = Tanzania\n| map_caption = \n| nickname = \n| location = [[Indian Ocean]]\n| additional_info = \n| coordinates = {{coord|6|7|9.81|S|39|9|56.06|E|type:isle_region:TZ-15|display=title,inline}}\n| archipelago = [[Zanzibar Archipelago]]\n| total_islands =\n| major_islands =\n| area_km2 = \n| length_km = 0.8\n| width_km = 0.23\n| highest_mount = \n| elevation_m = \n| population = \n| population_as_of =\n| density_km2 =\n| ethnic_groups =\n| country_admin_divisions_title     = Region\n| country_admin_divisions           = [[Zanzibar]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_1   =\n| country_admin_divisions_1         =\n| country_admin_divisions_title_2   =\n| country_admin_divisions_2         =\n| country_capital_city              = \n| country_largest_city              = \n| country_largest_city_population   =\n| country_leader_title              =\n| country_leader_name               =\n}}\n'''Changuu Island''' (also known as '''Kibandiko''', '''Prison''' or '''Quarantine Island''') is a small island 5.6&nbsp;km northwest of [[Stone Town]], [[Unguja]], [[Zanzibar]].  The island is around 800m long and 230m wide at its broadest point.<ref name=\"private\"/>  The island saw use as a prison for rebellious slaves in 1860s and also functioned as a [[coral]] mine.  \n\nThe [[United Kingdom|British]] [[First Minister]] of Zanzibar, [[Lloyd Mathews]], purchased the island in 1893 and constructed a prison complex there.  No prisoners were ever housed on the island and instead it became a [[quarantine]] station for [[yellow fever]] cases.  The station was only occupied for around half of the year and the rest of the time it was a popular holiday destination.  More recently, the island has become a government-owned tourist resort and houses a collection of endangered [[Aldabra giant tortoise]]s which were originally a gift from the [[United Kingdom|British]] governor of the [[Seychelles]].\n[[File:Prison island.jpg|The Island as seen from the Indian Ocean|thumb|800px|left]]\n\n== History ==\nChanguu is named after the [[Swahili language|Swahili]] name of a fish which is common in the seas around it, though it is shown as \"Kibandiko Island\" on some older maps, but this name is no longer used.<ref name=\"private\">{{cite web  | last = Changuu Private Island Paradise  | title = History  | url = http://www.privateislands-zanzibar.com/changuu/changuu-private-island-history.php  | accessdate = 2008-03-13  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080322213233/http://www.privateislands-zanzibar.com/changuu/changuu-private-island-history.php  | archive-date = 2008-03-22  | url-status = dead  }}</ref><ref name=\"travel\"/>  The island was uninhabited until the 1860s when the first [[Sultan of Zanzibar|Sultan]] of Zanzibar, [[Majid bin Said of Zanzibar|Majid bin Said]], gave it to two [[Arab]]s who used it as a prison for rebellious slaves prior to shipping them abroad or selling them at the slave market in Zanzibar's [[Stone Town]].<ref name=\"tourist\">{{cite web  | last = Zanzibar Commission for Tourism |title=Dhow Cruising  | url = http://www.zanzibartourism.net/dhowcruising.php | accessdate = 2008-03-15}}</ref>  \n\nZanzibar became a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[protectorate]] following the 1890 [[Heligoland-Zanzibar Treaty]] with [[Germany]], this resulted in the appointment of a British [[First Minister]], [[Lloyd Mathews]], in October 1891.<ref name=\"pouwels164\">{{Harvnb|Pouwels|1987|p=164}}.</ref><ref name=\"DNB\">{{Cite encyclopedia |last=Milne |first=Lynne  |contribution=Lloyd Mathews |title=[[Dictionary of National Biography]] |contribution-url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/34936 |ref=harv}}</ref>  Mathews purchased Changuu from its Arab owners on behalf of the Zanzibar government in 1893 with the intention of building a prison upon it.<ref name=\"private\"/>  The prison was to have housed violent and [[recidivism|recidivist]] criminals from the part of the African mainland which was then under the jurisdiction of Zanzibar.<ref name=\"tourist\"/>  Despite the prison buildings being completed in 1894, causing the island to become known commonly as \"Prison Island\", the facility never housed prisoners.<ref name=\"private\"/>\n\nThe British authorities were concerned by the risk of disease epidemics affecting Stone Town, then [[East Africa]]'s main port.  To combat this threat Changuu was turned into a [[quarantine]] island serving all of the British territories in East Africa.  The old prison was converted into the facility's hospital and in 1923 the island was officially renamed Quarantine Island.<ref name=\"private\"/>  Quarantine cases would be taken from the ships and monitored on the island for between one and two weeks before being allowed to progress with their journey.<ref name=\"travel\">{{cite web  | last = McIntyre  | first = Chris  | authorlink =   | coauthors =   | title = Islands near Zanzibar Town| work =   Zanzibar Travel Guide| publisher = Bradt Travel Guides  | year = 2006  | url = http://www.zanzibar-travel-guide.com/bradt_guide.asp?bradt=1918 | format =   | doi =   | accessdate = 2008-03-13}}</ref>  The main disease that was monitored was [[Yellow Fever]].<ref name=\"tourist\"/>  \n\nShips typically only arrived in East Africa during the period running from December to March and so the island was usually empty of quarantine cases for a large part of the year.<ref name=\"private\"/>  During the empty period the island became a popular leisure resort for European people and local residents of Zanzibar.  A building, known as the European Bungalow, was built in the late 1890s to cater for the holiday makers although the number of visitors had to be limited as the only freshwater on the island was rainwater stored in underground tanks.<ref name=\"private\"/>  Large pits on the island remained from earlier coral mining for use as a construction material and these pits were cleaned out and used as swimming pools.<ref name=\"travel\"/>  A new complex of quarantine buildings was erected in the south-west of the island in 1931 which gave an improved quarantine capacity of 904 persons.<ref name=\"private\"/>\n\n== Giant tortoises ==\n[[File:Aldabra giant tortoises on Changuu.jpg|Giant tortoises on the Island|thumb]]\n[[File:Aldabra Giant Tortoise Geochelone gigantea edit1.jpg|thumb|right|An Aldabra giant tortoise from Zanzibar]]\nIn 1919 the British governor of [[Seychelles]] sent a gift of four [[Aldabra giant tortoise]]s to Changuu from the island of [[Aldabra]].<ref name=\"private\"/>  These tortoises bred quickly and by 1955 they numbered around 200 animals.  However people began to steal the tortoises for sale abroad as pets or for food and their numbers dropped rapidly.  By 1988 there were around 100 tortoises, fifty in 1990 and just seven by 1996.<ref name=\"travel\"/>  A further 80 hatchlings were taken to the island in 1996 to increase the numbers but 40 of them vanished.  The Zanzibar government, with assistance from the [[World Society for the Protection of Animals]] (Now known as [[World Animal Protection]]) built a large compound for the protection of the animals and by 2000 numbers had recovered to 17 adults, 50 juveniles and 90 hatchlings.  \n\nThe species is now considered [[Vulnerable species|vulnerable]] and has been placed on the [[IUCN Red List]] by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]].  More tortoises, mainly juveniles, continue to be brought to the island from other locations for conservation.<ref name=\"travel\"/>  There is a dedicated foundation on the island which looks after the tortoises' welfare.<ref name=\"private\"/>  Visitors are able to observe and feed the tortoises.<ref name=\"travel\"/>\n\n== Changuu today ==\n\nThe island lost its use as a quarantine station, but remained in the ownership of the government who converted the newer quarantine buildings into a guesthouse.<ref name=\"private\"/>  This ceased to function but has since been reopened as a hotel by a private company.<ref name=\"travel\"/>  There are 15 holiday cottages in the northwest of the island as well as a tennis court, swimming pool and library and the old European Bungalow has been turned into a restaurant named after Mathews.<ref name=\"private\"/>  Freshwater is transported to the island via an underwater pipe from the Zanzibar mainland.<ref name=\"private\"/>  \n\nThe island is still owned by the government, which charges a US$4 entry fee.<ref name=\"travel\"/>  The old prison remains standing, providing shelter for some of the tortoises and the cells can be visited.<ref name=\"tourist\"/><ref name=\"planet\">{{cite web  | last = Planet Aware  | title = Changuu Island| url = http://www.planetware.com/zanzibar/changuu-island-tza-zza-chang.htm  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320073118/http://www.planetware.com/zanzibar/changuu-island-tza-zza-chang.htm|archivedate=2012-03-20|accessdate=2015-05-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{Cite book|last1=Pouwels|first1=Randall L|title=Horn and Crescent: Cultural Change and Traditional Islam on the East African Coast, 800-1900|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|year=1987|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iyw-_NMk0bgC|isbn=0-521-52309-5|ref=harv|postscript=<!--None-->}}.\n\n[[Category:Islands of Zanzibar]]\n[[Category:Zanzibar City]]\n[[Category:Prison islands]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "hatnote", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Changuu"}
{"title_page": "NAVGTR Award for Direction in a Game Cinema", "text_new": "The [[NAVGTR Awards|NAVGTR Award]] for Direction in a game Cinema is an award regulated by NAVGTR since its inception in 2001.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://navgtr.org/2001-awards/|title=2001 Awards {{!}} NAVGTR|last=|first=|date=|website=National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It recognizes the craft of visual storytelling through the use of [[animation]], frame composition, scene staging, and camera movement in video games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://navgtr.org/entries/award-category-descriptions/|title=Categories {{!}} NAVGTR|last=|first=|date=|website=National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n= Awards list by year =\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Category\n!Winner\n!Nominees\n!Recipient(s)\n!Developer\n|-\n|[[2001 in video gaming|2001]]\n|Direction in a Game Cinema\n|''[[Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty]]''<ref name=\":0\" />\n|''[[Devil May Cry (video game)|Devil May Cry]]'' ([[Hideki Kamiya]])<br />''[[Final Fantasy X]]'' ([[Motomu Toriyama]] (event), Takayoshi Nakazato (map), [[Toshiro Tsuchida]] (battle))<br />''[[Oddworld: Munch's Oddysee]]'' (Farzad Varahramyan)<br />''[[Onimusha: Warlords]]'' ([[Shimako Sato]], Ryu Kaneda)\n|So Toyota (ewp), [[Kyle Cooper]] (ewp), Ellerey Gave (ewp), Jennifer Gallo (ewp), Asa Hammond (ewp), Ben Lopez (ewp), Christian Severin (ewp)\n|[[Konami]]\n|-\n|[[2002 in video gaming|2002]]\n|Direction in a Game Cinema\n|''[[Grand Theft Auto: Vice City]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://navgtr.org/2002-awards/|title=2002 Awards {{!}} NAVGTR|last=|first=|date=|website=National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n|''[[Hitman 2: Silent Assassin]]''<br />''[[Kingdom Hearts (video game)|Kingdom Hearts]]'' ([[Tetsuya