anada, Nova Scotia, and New Brunswick, and the colonies of Newfoundland and Prince Edward Island ...''], London: [[s.n.]], 1867? [Resolutions of the Quebec Conference of October 10, 1864, and those of the London Conference of December 4, 1866, side by side]\n*{{cite book |author=Nova Scotia. House of Assembly |title=Debate on the union of the provinces, in the House of Assembly of Nova Scotia, March 16th, 18th and 19th, 1867 |year=1867 |url=http://www.canadiana.org/afficher/67163/2}}\n*{{cite book |first1=Joseph |last1=Howe |first2=William |last2=Annand |first3=Hugh |last3=McDonald |author4=Great Britain. Foreign Office |title=Letter addressed to the Earl of Carnarvon by Mr. Joseph Howe, Mr. William Annand, and Mr. Hugh McDonald, stating their objections to the proposed scheme of union of the British North American provinces |url=http://www.canadiana.org/afficher/04679/4 |year=1867 |publisher=Printed by G.E. Eyre and W. Spottiswoode, for H.M. Stationery Off. |page=36}}\n*{{cite book |author1=Canada. Parliament |first2=Murray A. |last2=Lapin |author3=Canada. Archives branch |author4=J. S. Patrick |title=Parliamentary debates on the subject of the Confederation of the British North American provinces, 3rd session, 8th provincial Parliament of Canada |url=https://archive.org/details/parliamentaryde09parlgoog |year=1865 |publisher=Hunter, Rose & co., parliamentary printers}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Canadian Confederation}}\n*[http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/confederation/index-e.html Library and Archives Canada.gov: Canadian Confederation collection] \n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111230022553/http://www.canadiana.ca/citm/themes/constitution/constitution12_e.html Canadiana: \"On the Road to Confederation\"] \n*[http://www.mccord-museum.qc.ca/en/keys/webtours/GE_P1_2_EN.html McCord Museum: \"Confederation: The Creation of Canada\"]\n*[http://biographi.ca/en/theme_conferences_1864.html?p=1 ''Dictionary of Canadian Biography,'' \"The Charlottetown and Quebec Conferences of 1864\"]\n\n{{Constitution of Canada|Confederation}}\n{{History of Canada navbox}}\n{{Portal bar|History|Canada|Politics}}\n\n[[Category:Canadian Confederation| ]]\n[[Category:1840s in Canada]]\n[[Category:1850s in Canada]]\n[[Category:1860s in Canada]]\n[[Category:1867 in Canada]]\n[[Category:Federalism in Canada]]\n[[Category:History of Canada]]\n[[Category:National unifications]]\n[[Category:Political history of Canada]]\n[[Category:British North America]]\n[[Category:Pre-Confederation Canada]]\n[[Category:Post-Confederation Canada (1867\u20131914)]]\n[[Category:1867 establishments in Canada|*]]\n[[Category:1867 in Canadian law]]\n[[Category:1867 in politics]]\n[[Category:19th century in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "2607:fea8:bee1:380:c466:e135:e226:3db7", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eColonial organization)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canadian_Confederation"}
{"title_page": "Shaikh Jamiruddin", "text_new": "{{short description|Writer and religious preacher}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n| name           = Shaikh Jamiruddin\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| religion       = [[Islam]]\n| denomination   = \n| alias          = \n| location       = \n| Title          = \n| Period         = \n| Predecessor    = \n| Successor      = \n| ordination     = \n| post           = \n| previous_post  = \n| present_post   = \n| birth_date     = 1870\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = 2 June 1937 (aged 67)\n| death_place    = \n}}\n'''Shaikh Jamiruddin''' (1870 \u2013 2 June 1937) was a writer and [[Islamic]] preacher.\n\n==Biography==\nJamiruddin was born on 1870 in the village of Garadobe Bahadurpur of [[Gangni Upazila|Gangni]] of [[Meherpur District|Meherpur]].<ref name=a>{{Cite Banglapedia|article=Jamiruddin, Shaikh|author=Shamsul Alam, Muhammad\n}}</ref> He studied in Meherpur Amjhupi Christian School and Krishnanagar Normal School. He converted to Christianity in 1887.<ref name=a/> After that he changed his name into John Jamiruddin.\n\nJamiruddin graduated from St. Paul's Divinity College, Allahabad in theology in 1891.<ref name=a/> Later, he got admitted into Divinity College, Kolkata. He studied Christianity and Sanskrit, Arabic, Greek and Hebrew literature and grammar from there.<ref name=a/> He knew [[Bangla language|Bangla]],  [[English language|English]], [[Urdu language|Urdu]],  [[Persian language|Persian]] and  [[Latin language|Latin]].\n\nJamiruddin wrote an article titled ''Asol Koran Kothay'' in the ''Khristiyo Bandhob'' on June 1892.<ref name=b/> In reply [[Munshi\u00a0Mohammad\u00a0Meherullah]] wrote an article titled ''Isayi Ba Khristani Dhoka Bhonjon'' that was published in the ''[[The Sudhakar|Sudhakar]]'' on 20 and 27 June 1892 where he gave the answers of his six questions.<ref name=c/>\n\nLater, Jamiruddin wrote an article the ''[[The Sudhakar|Sudhakor]]''.<ref name=b/> In reply [[Munshi\u00a0Mohammad\u00a0Meherullah]] wrote an article titled ''Asol Koran Sorbotro''.<ref name=c>{{cite web|url=https://www.alokitobangladesh.com/todays/details/77763/2014/06/08?__cf_chl_jschl_tk__=b433839fdda7b83bfe2a94ecc97bcfa1af6ae523-1578454133-0-AeW5TnPMkeLYftMWjyD_b3WN21nlSVtvFR1RaLReMEVu0QatCICfDp3FJc1XizRTjVYPujmJjoy3oXho2DbTLXbPl9neREXMQIxzYI378Ec4beFR50r-4lw1-l2C9nRKBemGibr-_MQOHS6cNLzC7bMZWR8IwY48qKyTws39dsU4h9xp6Mn2ozIYFpP3djkuS_HBgxY-NcYA45UcJl8fQ67ZiBcaVxifYrcUwkvBxyeiNoEHfS3WBcjil9C11ujAKyVpDjT4cW_yjgMmqcBFDjCMAEKTg6E3nfoXIiB0-l-gvY_rAcpGJFnaoCljlBM3HA|title=\u09b8\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09af\u09bf\u0995 \u0993 \u09b8\u0982\u09b8\u09cd\u0995\u09be\u09b0\u0995 \u09ac\u09be\u0997\u09cd\u09ae\u09c0 \u09ae\u09c1\u09a8\u09b6\u09c0 \u09ae\u09c7\u09b9\u09c7\u09b0\u09c1\u09b2\u09cd\u09b2\u09be\u09b9|date=8 June 2014|accessdate=8 January 2020|website=Alokito Bangladesh|language=bn}}</ref> After reading this article Jamiruddin decided to convert himself into [[Islam]].<ref name=b>{{cite web|url=http://www.jessore.gov.bd/site/page/bf3f6eaf-1c4a-11e7-8f57-286ed488c766/\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u0996\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09a4%20\u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09ac|title=\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u0996\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09a4 \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09ac|accessdate=8 January 2020|website=www.jessore.gov.bd|language=bn}}</ref>\n\nJamiruddin wrote books on religious issue. He translated and wrote books on social issues too. He wrote books like ''Hazrat Isa Ke'', ''Meher Charit'', ''Islami Baktrita'', ''Shrestha Nabi Hazrat Mohammad (SM)'', ''Padrir Dhokavonjon'' and more.<ref name=a/> He wrote an autobiography titled ''Amar Jiboni O Islam Grahan Brittanto''.\n\nJamiruddin died on 2 June 1937.<ref name=a/> He was buried in his family graveyard.\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jamiruddin, Shaikh}}\n[[Category:Bengali Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Meherpur District]]\n[[Category:Converts to Christianity from Islam]]\n[[Category:Converts to Islam from Christianity]]\n[[Category:Bengali writers]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi translators]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Writer and religious preacher}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n| name           = Shaikh Jamiruddin\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| religion       = [[Islam]]\n| denomination   = \n| alias          = \n| location       = \n| Title          = \n| Period         = \n| Predecessor    = \n| Successor      = \n| ordination     = \n| post           = \n| previous_post  = \n| present_post   = \n| birth_date     = 1870\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = 2 June 1937 (aged 67)\n| death_place    = \n}}\n'''Shaikh Jamiruddin''' (1870 \u2013 2 June 1937) was a writer and [[Islamic]] preacher.\n\n==Biography==\nJamiruddin was born on 1870 in the village of Garadobe Bahadurpur of [[Gangni Upazila|Gangni]] of [[Meherpur District|Meherpur]].<ref name=a>{{Cite Banglapedia|article=Jamiruddin, Shaikh|author=Shamsul Alam, Muhammad\n}}</ref> He studied in Meherpur Amjhupi Christian School and Krishnanagar Normal School. He converted to Christianity in 1887.<ref name=a/> After that he changed his name into John Jamiruddin.\n\nJamiruddin graduated from St. Paul's Divinity College, Allahabad in theology in 1891.<ref name=a/> Later, he got admitted into Divinity College, Kolkata. He studied Christianity and Sanskrit, Arabic, Greek and Hebrew literature and grammar from there.<ref name=a/> He knew [[Bangla language|Bangla]],  [[English language|English]], [[Urdu language|Urdu]],  [[Persian language|Persian]] and  [[Latin language|Latin]].\n\nJamiruddin wrote an article titled ''Asol Koran Kothay'' in the ''Khristiyo Bandhob'' on June 1892.<ref name=b/> In reply [[Munshi\u00a0Mohammad\u00a0Meherullah]] wrote an article titled ''Isayi Ba Khristani Dhoka Bhonjon'' that was published in the ''[[The Sudhakar|Sudhakar]]'' on 20 and 27 June 1892 where he gave the answers of his six questions.<ref name=c/>\n\nLater, Jamiruddin wrote an article the ''[[The Sudhakar|Sudhakor]]''.<ref name=b/> In reply [[Munshi\u00a0Mohammad\u00a0Meherullah]] wrote an article titled ''Asol Koran Sorbotro''.<ref name=c>{{cite web|url=https://www.alokitobangladesh.com/todays/details/77763/2014/06/08?__cf_chl_jschl_tk__=b433839fdda7b83bfe2a94ecc97bcfa1af6ae523-1578454133-0-AeW5TnPMkeLYftMWjyD_b3WN21nlSVtvFR1RaLReMEVu0QatCICfDp3FJc1XizRTjVYPujmJjoy3oXho2DbTLXbPl9neREXMQIxzYI378Ec4beFR50r-4lw1-l2C9nRKBemGibr-_MQOHS6cNLzC7bMZWR8IwY48qKyTws39dsU4h9xp6Mn2ozIYFpP3djkuS_HBgxY-NcYA45UcJl8fQ67ZiBcaVxifYrcUwkvBxyeiNoEHfS3WBcjil9C11ujAKyVpDjT4cW_yjgMmqcBFDjCMAEKTg6E3nfoXIiB0-l-gvY_rAcpGJFnaoCljlBM3HA|title=\u09b8\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09af\u09bf\u0995 \u0993 \u09b8\u0982\u09b8\u09cd\u0995\u09be\u09b0\u0995 \u09ac\u09be\u0997\u09cd\u09ae\u09c0 \u09ae\u09c1\u09a8\u09b6\u09c0 \u09ae\u09c7\u09b9\u09c7\u09b0\u09c1\u09b2\u09cd\u09b2\u09be\u09b9|date=8 June 2014|accessdate=8 January 2020|website=Alokito Bangladesh|language=bn}}</ref> After reading this article Jamiruddin decided to convert himself into [[Islam]].<ref name=b>{{cite web|url=http://www.jessore.gov.bd/site/page/bf3f6eaf-1c4a-11e7-8f57-286ed488c766/\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u0996\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09a4%20\u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09ac|title=\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u0996\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09a4 \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09ac|accessdate=8 January 2020|website=www.jessore.gov.bd|language=bn}}</ref>\n\nJamiruddin wrote books on religious issue. He translated and wrote books on social issues too. He wrote books like ''Hazrat Isa Ke'', ''Meher Charit'', ''Islami Baktrita'', ''Shrestha Nabi Hazrat Mohammad (SM)'', ''Padrir Dhokavonjon'' and more.<ref name=a/> He wrote an autobiography titled ''Amar Jiboni O Islam Grahan Brittanto''.\n\nJamiruddin died on 2 June 1937.<ref name=a/> He was buried in his family graveyard.\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jamiruddin, Shaikh}}\n\n[[Category:Bengali Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Meherpur District]]\n[[Category:Converts to Christianity from Islam]]\n[[Category:Converts to Islam from Christianity]]\n[[Category:Bengali writers]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi translators]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shaikh_Jamiruddin"}
{"title_page": "All Yesterdays", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox book|<!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name = All Yesterdays\n| title_orig = \n| translator = \n| image = All Yesterdays cover.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Cover, depicting three ''[[Protoceratops]]'' in a tree.\n| author = [[John Conway (palaeoartist)|John Conway]], [[C. M. Kosemen]], and [[Darren Naish]]\n| illustrator = \n| country = United Kingdom\n| language = English\n| subject = [[Palaeoart]]\n| series = \n| publisher = Irregular Books\n| release_date = 2012\n| media_type = Print, digital\n| pages = 100 pp.\n| isbn = 978-1291177121\n| oclc = \n}}\n'''''All Yesterdays: Unique and Speculative Views of Dinosaurs and Other Prehistoric Animals''''' is a 2012 [[art book]] on the [[paleoart|palaeoartistic]] reconstruction of [[dinosaurs]] and other extinct animals by [[John_Conway_(palaeoartist)|John Conway]], [[C. M. Kosemen]] and [[Darren Naish]]. One of its central tenets concerns the fact that many dinosaur reconstructions are outdated, overly conservative, and inconsistent with the variation observed in modern animals.<ref name=\"witton2018\">{{cite book | last=Witton|first=Mark P.|title=The Palaeoartist's Handbook: Recreating prehistoric animals in art|year=2018|publisher=The Crowood Press Ltd.|authorlink= Mark P. Witton|location=U.K.: Ramsbury|isbn=978-1785004612}}</ref> Writing for ''The Guardian'', palaeontologist David Hone summarises its focus as an exploration of views of dinosaurs and related animals that unusual and sometimes even confusing to viewers, but which are well within the bounds of behaviour, anatomy and soft tissue that we see in living animals. \"... the key point is that they are in many ways no more extreme or unlikely that what we see in living species of birds, mammals and reptiles, and no less plausible than many more 'traditional' views of dinosaurs.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hone|first1=David|title=All Yesterdays - book review|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/lost-worlds/2013/mar/24/dinosaurs-fossils|work=The Guardian|date=24 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nThe book first recounts the history of changing perceptions of dinosaurs as expressed in artwork. It begins with the sluggish and slow dinosaurs seen in the works of [[Charles R. Knight]], and then continues into analyzing reconstructions after the [[dinosaur renaissance]]. It points out that these reconstructions do not take the often bizarre [[Integumentary system|integumentary coverings]] of living animals into account, and that dinosaurs should be portrayed as natural animals that aren't 'shrink-wrapped' with many of the individual bones visible.\n\nThe remainder of the book consists of pictures with accompanying explanatory texts. Each picture displays a hypothetical adaptation that an extinct animal could have possessed, such as a [[plesiosaur]] disguised on the seafloor like a [[wobbegong]] or something that dinosaurs aren't usually shown doing, such as a sleeping ''[[Tyrannosaurus]]''. The texts describe the adaptations or habits and explain why they are plausible. Some of the entries are deliberately made to break a paleoartistic clich\u00e9, such as a ''[[Tenontosaurus]]'' walking alone without a predatory ''[[Deinonychus]]'' in sight (''Tenontosaurus'' is almost exclusively depicted in dinosaur art as the prey of ''Deinonychus'').\n\nThe second and last major section of the book is titled \"All Todays\", and depicts animals from the present day as if non-human paleontologists from the future were reconstructing them from fossilized skeletons. Some of the creatures are somewhat recognizable, like a [[vulture]] depicted with [[pterosaur]]-like wings; others are completely unrecognizable, like a [[rhinoceros]] reconstructed with no nose horn and a sail instead of a hump. By showing how completely extant animals might be misunderstood if known only from skeletal remains, ''All Yesterdays'' shows that our own conceptions of extinct animals are likely equally mistaken.\n\n==Reception==\n\n''All Yesterdays'' has received mostly very enthusiastic reviews from palaeontologists, and is perceived as introducing or popularising a new \"third wave\" approach to palaeoart after the classical period of Knight, [[Rudolph F. Zallinger|Zallinger]], [[Zden\u011bk Burian|Burian]] and others, and the more modern work of [[Robert T. Bakker|Bakker]], [[Gregory S. Paul|Paul]], [[Doug Henderson (artist)|Henderson]] and others. For example, John Hutchinson of the Royal Veterinary College wrote \"This is a thinking person\u2019s book ... for rumination, to challenge your preconceptions, not to have a flashy coffee table book. It\u2019s not eye candy \u2014 it\u2019s more like brain jerky.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hutchinson|first1=John|title=Yes- another day, another positive \"All Yesterdays\" book review|url=http://whatsinjohnsfreezer.com/2013/03/17/all-yesterdays-review/|website=What's In John's Freezer?|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> And Mike Taylor wrote \"''All Yesterdays'' is not only the most beautiful but also the most important palaeoart book of the last four decades\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Taylor|first1=Mike|title=Review: All Yesterdays (Conway, Kosemen and Naish)|url=http://svpow.com/2012/11/29/review-all-yesterdays-conway-koseman-and-naish/|website=Sauropod Vertebra Picture of the Week|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nSubsequent to its publication, ''All Yesterdays'' and its associated concepts have sometimes appeared in publications covering the nature, history, and 'best practices' of palaeoart, particularly in the context of emphasizing the need for modern depictions of dinosaurs to be consistent with how living animals look and behave.<ref>{{Cite book | last=Witton |first=Mark P. |title=Recreating an Age of Reptiles |year=2016|publisher=Crowood Press |authorlink= Mark P. Witton |isbn=978-1785003349}}</ref> This 'post modern' approach to palaeoart is thought to be seminal in the modern culture of identifying and subverting overused palaeoart 'memes' and tropes, and may be an accurate reflection of the \"contemporary mood of palaeoartists more than any other project.\"<ref name=\"witton2018\"></ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Speculative evolution]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2012 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Dinosaur books]]\n[[Category:Speculative evolution]]\n[[Category:Paleoart]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox book|<!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name = All Yesterdays\n| title_orig = \n| translator = \n| image = All Yesterdays cover.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Cover, depicting three ''[[Protoceratops]]'' in a tree.\n| author = [[John Conway (palaeoartist)|John Conway]], [[C. M. Kosemen]], and [[Darren Naish]]\n| illustrator = \n| country = United Kingdom\n| language = English\n| subject = [[Palaeoart]]\n| series = \n| publisher = Irregular Books\n| release_date = 2012\n| media_type = Print, digital\n| pages = 100 pp.\n| isbn = 978-1291177121\n| oclc = \n}}\n'''''All Yesterdays: Unique and Speculative Views of Dinosaurs and Other Prehistoric Animals''''' is a 2012 [[art book]] on the [[paleoart|palaeoartistic]] reconstruction of [[dinosaurs]] and other extinct animals by [[John_Conway_(palaeoartist)|John Conway]], [[C. M. Kosemen]] and [[Darren Naish]]. One of its central tenets concerns the fact that many dinosaur reconstructions are outdated, overly conservative, and inconsistent with the variation observed in modern animals.<ref name=\"witton2018\">{{cite book | last=Witton|first=Mark P.|title=The Palaeoartist's Handbook: Recreating prehistoric animals in art|year=2018|publisher=The Crowood Press Ltd.|authorlink= Mark P. Witton|location=U.K.: Ramsbury|isbn=978-1785004612}}</ref> Writing for ''The Guardian'', palaeontologist David Hone summarises its focus as an exploration of views of dinosaurs and related animals that unusual and sometimes even confusing to viewers, but which are well within the bounds of behaviour, anatomy and soft tissue that we see in living animals. \"... the key point is that they are in many ways no more extreme or unlikely that what we see in living species of birds, mammals and reptiles, and no less plausible than many more 'traditional' views of dinosaurs.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hone|first1=David|title=All Yesterdays - book review|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/lost-worlds/2013/mar/24/dinosaurs-fossils|work=The Guardian|date=24 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nThe book first recounts the history of changing perceptions of dinosaurs as expressed in artwork. It begins with the sluggish and slow dinosaurs seen in the works of [[Charles R. Knight]], and then continues into analyzing reconstructions after the [[dinosaur renaissance]]. It points out that these reconstructions do not take the often bizarre [[Integumentary system|integumentary coverings]] of living animals into account, and that dinosaurs should be portrayed as natural animals that aren't 'shrink-wrapped' with many of the individual bones visible.\n\nThe remainder of the book consists of pictures with accompanying explanatory texts. Each picture displays a hypothetical adaptation that an extinct animal could have possessed, such as a [[plesiosaur]] disguised on the seafloor like a [[wobbegong]] or something that dinosaurs aren't usually shown doing, such as a sleeping ''[[Tyrannosaurus]]''. The texts describe the adaptations or habits and explain why they are plausible. Some of the entries are deliberately made to break a paleoartistic clich\u00e9, such as a ''[[Tenontosaurus]]'' walking alone without a predatory ''[[Deinonychus]]'' in sight (''Tenontosaurus'' is almost exclusively depicted in dinosaur art as the prey of ''Deinonychus'').\n\nThe second and last major section of the book is titled \"All Todays\", and depicts animals from the present day as if non-human paleontologists from the future were reconstructing them from fossilized skeletons. Some of the creatures are somewhat recognizable, like a [[vulture]] depicted with [[pterosaur]]-like wings; others are completely unrecognizable, like a [[rhinoceros]] reconstructed with no nose horn and a sail instead of a hump. By showing how completely extant animals might be misunderstood if known only from skeletal remains, ''All Yesterdays'' shows that our own conceptions of extinct animals are likely equally mistaken.\n\n==Reception==\n\n''All Yesterdays'' has received mostly very enthusiastic reviews from palaeontologists, and is perceived as introducing or popularising a new \"third wave\" approach to palaeoart after the classical period of Knight, [[Rudolph F. Zallinger|Zallinger]], [[Zden\u011bk Burian|Burian]] and others, and the more modern work of [[Robert T. Bakker|Bakker]], [[Gregory S. Paul|Paul]], [[Doug Henderson (artist)|Henderson]] and others. For example, John Hutchinson of the Royal Veterinary College wrote \"This is a thinking person\u2019s book ... for rumination, to challenge your preconceptions, not to have a flashy coffee table book. It\u2019s not eye candy \u2014 it\u2019s more like brain jerky.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hutchinson|first1=John|title=Yes- another day, another positive \"All Yesterdays\" book review|url=http://whatsinjohnsfreezer.com/2013/03/17/all-yesterdays-review/|website=What's In John's Freezer?|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> And Mike Taylor wrote \"''All Yesterdays'' is not only the most beautiful but also the most important palaeoart book of the last four decades\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Taylor|first1=Mike|title=Review: All Yesterdays (Conway, Kosemen and Naish)|url=http://svpow.com/2012/11/29/review-all-yesterdays-conway-koseman-and-naish/|website=Sauropod Vertebra Picture of the Week|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nSubsequent to its publication, ''All Yesterdays'' and its associated concepts have sometimes appeared in publications covering the nature, history, and 'best practices' of palaeoart, particularly in the context of emphasizing the need for modern depictions of dinosaurs to be consistent with how living animals look and behave.<ref>{{Cite book | last=Witton |first=Mark P. |title=Recreating an Age of Reptiles |year=2016|publisher=Crowood Press |authorlink= Mark P. Witton |isbn=978-1785003349}}</ref> This 'post modern' approach to palaeoart is thought to be seminal in the modern culture of identifying and subverting overused palaeoart 'memes' and tropes, and may be an accurate reflection of the \"contemporary mood of palaeoartists more than any other project.\"<ref name=\"witton 2018\"></ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Speculative evolution]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2012 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Dinosaur books]]\n[[Category:Speculative evolution]]\n[[Category:Paleoart]]\n", "name_user": "Ferahgo the Assassin", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/All_Yesterdays"}
